SupervisionCfg group node

Group object node SupervisionCfg is used to configure leandc serial port or socket real-time traffic monitoring and also enables serial server functionality. Real-time traffic monitoring and serial server functionality has designated supervision instances which are configured under SupervisionCfg group node, please refer to the sample below containing 4 different supervision instances.

<SupervisionCfg>
     <MONRAW SrcHWIndex="1" DstHWIndex="51" Name="Raw monitoring instance"/>
     <MONCOMP SrcHWIndex="2" DstHWIndex="52" SrvHWIndex="53" Name="Compatible mon instance"/>
     <REDIRECT SrcHWIndex="4" DstHWIndex="61" Name="UART redirect instance"/>
     <OVERRIDE SrcHWIndex="3" DstHWIndex="62" SrvHWIndex="63" Name="UART override instance"/>
</SupervisionCfg>

Every supervision instance has a unique element node and its configuration is described in the following paragraphs.

Important

Supervision instances must be listed under SupervisionCfg group node in the following order:
MONRAW
MONCOMP
REDIRECT
OVERRIDE

MONRAW

Traffic through any leandc serial port or socket can be captured and sent to a remote destination for a real time monitoring. Remote traffic monitoring can be enabled using so called ‘raw monitoring’ supervision instance which requires only 1 destination socket to send the captured data. Raw monitoring mode will be active as long as there is a traffic through the monitored port and remote destination is reachable. Please see sample MONRAW element node used to configure raw monitoring and the table listing all available attributes below.

<MONRAW SrcHWIndex="1" DstHWIndex="51" Name="Raw monitoring instance"/>
Table 2.21 Leandc MONRAW node
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1...254 Source index of the hardware node to be monitored. Any of UART; TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as a source for traffic monitoring.
DstHWIndex 1...254 Destination index of the hardware node to send captured traffic. Any of TCPSERVER or UDP nodes can be used to send captured traffic as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 100 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

UDP socket is recommended as a destination for sending the captured traffic.
Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950.

MONCOMP

Traffic through any leandc serial port or socket can be captured and sent to a remote destination for a real time monitoring. Remote traffic monitoring can be enabled using so called ‘compatible monitoring’ supervision instance which requires 2 sockets for its operation. 1st socket will be the destination to send captured data and the 2nd socket will be used for service commands. Captured data will be sent only if both remote sockets are active/reachable. Please see sample MONCOMP element node used to configure compatible monitoring and the table listing all available attributes below.

<MONCOMP SrcHWIndex="2" DstHWIndex="52" SrvHWIndex="53" Name="Compatible monitoring instance"/>
Table 2.22 Leandc MONCOMP node
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1...254 Source index of the hardware node to be monitored. Any of UART; TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as a source for traffic monitoring.
DstHWIndex 1...254 Destination index of the hardware node to send captured traffic. Any of TCPSERVER or UDP nodes can be used to send the captured traffic as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
SrvHWIndex 1...254 Index of the hardware node for receiving service commands. Any of TCPCLIENT nodes can be used as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 100 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout attribute will be used to check activity of the service socket. The service TCPSERVER socket will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds and also the destination socket is disconnected/unreachable.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950 and service node (SrvHWIndex) is 64966.

REDIRECT

Serial server functionality enables to send data from one serial port to another over the network in a transparently as if these serial ports where connected together with a direct cable. In order to permanently enable serial server functionality in leandc so called ‘redirect’ supervision instance can be used. It requires only 1 destination socket to send the redirected data. Serial data will be redirected as long as remote destination is reachable. Please see sample REDIRECT element node used to configure serial server and the table listing all available attributes below.

<REDIRECT SrcHWIndex="4" DstHWIndex="61" Name="UART redirect instance"/>
Table 2.23 Leandc REDIRECT node
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1...254 Index of the UART node to be redirected. Data received through this UART will be redirected to a destination hardware node and data received from a destination hardware node will be redirected to this UART. No communication protocol instances must be linked to UART node in order to use it for redirection.
DstHWIndex 1...254 Destination index of the hardware node to redirect the data. Any of TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as destination. Data received from a destination hardware node will be redirected to UART.
Name Max 100 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout and TCPCLIENT.IdleTimeout attributes will be used to check activity of the destination socket. The destination TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds. This means there has to be an ongoing communication to prevent TCP sockets from being automatically disconnected. This doesn’t apply to UDP socket.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950.

OVERRIDE

Serial server functionality enables to send data from one serial port to another over network transparently as if these serial ports where connected together with a cable. Sometimes it is useful to enable serial server functionality only temporarily and return port to a normal operation when it is no longer needed. Temporary serial server functionality can be used to e.g. poll or configure a serial device connected to LEANDC and serial port has to resume normal operation afterwards. ‘Override’ supervision instance provides temporary override of the normal operation of the serial port enabling remote data to be transferred through this port. It requires 2 sockets for operation: 1st socket is destination for the redirected serial data and the 2nd socket is used for service commands. Serial server functionality will be automatically enabled only if both sockets are active/reachable. Please see sample OVERRIDE element node used to configure temporary serial server and the table listing all available attributes below.

<OVERRIDE SrcHWIndex="3" DstHWIndex="62" SrvHWIndex="63" Name="UART override instance"/>
Table 2.24 Leandc OVERRIDE node
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1...254 Index of the UART node to be temporarily overridden. Data received through this UART will be temporarily redirected to a destination hardware node and data received from a destination hardware node will be temporarily redirected to this UART.
DstHWIndex 1...254 Destination index of the hardware node to temporarily redirect the UART data. Any of TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as destination. Data received from a destination hardware node will be temporarily redirected to source UART.
SrvHWIndex 1...254 Index of the hardware node for receiving service commands. Any of TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT nodes can be used as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 100 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout and TCPCLIENT.IdleTimeout attributes will be used to check activity of both destination and service sockets. The destination and service TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds. Also the service TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a number of seconds configured in the destination socket UDP.IdleTimeout attribute. This means there has to be an ongoing communication to prevent TCP sockets from being automatically disconnected.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950 and service node (SrvHWIndex) is 64966.

3. IEC60870-5-101 Slave

This section describes how to configure IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance must have XML configuration file where its IO object table and additional protocol-related settings will be stored. One and the same XML configuration file can be used for multiple IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances, this becomes useful in case if identical IO objects need to be reported to several Master stations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC101sl_test.xml‘ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC101sl.XMLpath attribute of a communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC101sl_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-101 Slave configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC101sl_test.xml’) must have a root object node IEC101slConfig which has 6 child group object nodes VersionControl; ProtocolCfg; DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable please see the sample below.

<IEC101slConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC101sl" … version="1.00">
      <VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
      <ProtocolCfg>
         <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
         <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
         …
      </ProtocolCfg>
      <DITable>
         <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10"/>
         …
      </DITable>
      <AITable>
         <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="10" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0"/>
         …
      </AITable>
      <DOTable>
         <DO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
         …
      </DOTable>
      <AOTable>
         <AO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
         …
      </AOTable>
</IEC101slConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable group nodes compose an IO object table and they are common for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances. Please refer to the tables 5.1; 5.6; 5.10 and 5.14 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group node

ProtocolCfg group and its child element nodes contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg node and all available child element nodes below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element node.

<ProtocolCfg>
   <XMLSettings … />
   <LinkSettings … />
   <CommsSettings … />
   <ASDUSettings … />
   <ServiceSettings … />
   <Timeouts … />
   <TimeSettings … />
   <Periodic … />
   <BufferSizes … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 3.1 IEC60870-5-101 Slave XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings LinkAddrSize="1" ACDLinkStatusResp="0" ACDAlways="0" ClassIgnore="0" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 3.2 IEC60870-5-101 Slave LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

LinkAddrSize

 1 or 2 1 byte Link layer address size in bytes. Please note link address size of the protocol instances sharing the same hardware node must be the same.
ACDLinkStatusResp 0 0 [ACD] bit (link control field) value of the ‘status of link’ response message (no access demand)
1 [ACD] bit (link control field) value of the ‘status of link’ response message (access demand)
ACDAlways 0 0 [ACD] bit (link control field) in response messages gets set only if Class 1 data is available
1 [ACD] bit (link control field) in response messages is always set
ClassIgnore 0 0 Class of the received message is being used to determine either Class 1 or Class 2 data should be sent.
1 Class of the received message is ignored, Class 1 and Class 2 data is sent regardless of the requested Class. Please note this functionality is deviation from communication standard and option should be avoided.

Flags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See table 3.3 for description.
Table 3.3 IEC60870-5-101 Slave Link flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Link flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send variable and fixed length link layer messages as required. (First character of variable link layer message is - 0x68 and fixed length message - 0x10)
xxxx.xxx1 Send only variable length link layer messages
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Don’t use single character ACK and NACK responses (0xE5 and 0xA2)
xxxx.xx1x Use single character ACK and NACK responses (0xE5 and 0xA2)
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx [FCB] bit (link control field) must be zero in ‘status of link’ request received from Master station. Leandc will not reply to the ‘status of link’ request if [FCB] bit is set.
xxxx.x1xx [FCB] bit (link control field) is ignored in ‘status of link’ request received from Master station
Bits 3...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" StartupGIDelay="10" />
Table 3.4 IEC60870-5-101 Slave CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 1...232 - 1 60 sec Delay in seconds before resetting the link if there is no request from Master station. Reset remote link message is required after communication loss exceeding configured offline delay in order to restart communication.
StartupGIDelay 0...232 - 1 0 sec Incoming General interrogation commands are rejected for a configured number of seconds on leandc startup. Negative confirmation will be sent to General Interrogation requests received before the delay expires. This delay allows leandc to poll data from outstations for the first time on startup, before data is being requested by an upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings COTSize="1" CAASize="1" IOASize="2" InvalidEvent="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" DIEventType="2" AIEventType="14" DOType="46" AOType="50" DIInterDelay="8000" DIIndetDelay="3500" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" TimeSync="1" TranspTypes="1" ForwardGI="1" />
Table 3.5 IEC60870-5-101 Slave ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

COTSize

 1 or 2 1 byte Cause Of Transmission size in bytes including Originator address (default 1 byte - if originator address is not used)

CAASize

 1 or 2 1 byte Common address of ASDU size in bytes

IOASize

 1; 2 or 3 2 bytes Information Object Address size in bytes
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will be set (‘1’) to indicate last hour of the Summer Time before a clock adjustment at the end of the Daylight Saving Time (DST) (this is when clock is turned back one hour)
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will always be set (‘1’) if the date and time of the tag is Summer Time. Please note this functionality is deviation from communication standard and option should be avoided.
DIEventType See table 5.3 2 [M_SP_TA_1] Use this ASDU type to send DI events which don’t have DI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 2 – ‘Single-point Information’, DI event will be sent using ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min)
AIEventType See table 5.8 14 [M_ME_TC_1] Use this ASDU type to send AI events which don’t have AI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 14 – ‘Short floating point’, AI event will be sent using ASDU type 14 [M_ME_TC_1], CP24time2A, msec and min)
DOType See table 5.12 0 = any Only accept command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Single or Double command) if DO object doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
AOType See table 5.16 0 = any Only accept setpoint command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Normalized or Scaled setpoint) if AO object doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
DOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if DO object doesn’t have DO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
AOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if AO object doesn’t have AO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
DIInterDelay 0...232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.InterDelay attribute. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds)
DIIndetDelay 0...232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.IndetDelay attribute. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds)
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after system leandc
TimeSync 0 0 Reject incoming clock synchronization messages.
1 Accept incoming clock synchronization messages and synchronize internal real time clock. Please note internal real time clock will be synchronized immediately if a time difference between received time stamp and the internal clock is greater than 1 hour. If a time difference is less than 1 hour, internal clock will be adjusted only once an hour.

TranspTypes

 0 0 ASDU type of every DI/AI object is determined by XML configuration settings.
1 ASDU type of every DI/AI object will be made transparent whenever possible. The same ASDU type will be used to report DI/AI object to upstream station as received from downstream outstation, providing both source and destination communication protocol instances are compatible. Otherwise default ASDU type will be used. Please note object will be excluded from General Interrogation response before it is received from downstream outstation on leandc startup. This is because it is impossible to determine ASDU type of the object before is has been received from outstation.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control quality flags of the DI/AI events generated when outstation goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings NotInitFlags="0x80" DisabledFlags="0x80" OfflineFlags="0x40" PostOfflineFlags="0x80" EventMask="0x00" />
Table 3.6 IEC60870-5-101 Slave ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NotInitFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. See table 3.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires on leandc startup. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
DisabledFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station gets Disabled with a Service command. See table 3.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station gets Disabled. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
OfflineFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station state changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires) See table 3.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when OfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
PostOfflineFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers after PostOfflineDelay timer expires. See table 3.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when PostOfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
EventMask 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See table 3.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 3.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
Bits 4...7 Any Bits reserved for future use
Table 3.8 DI/AI qualifier quality bits
Bits Value Description
Quality bits [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DI/AI qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will not be set
xxx1.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will be set
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will not be set
xx1x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will be set
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will not be set
x1xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will be set
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will not be set
1xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will be set
Bits 0...3 xxxx.0000 Bits are used for Single/Double status information and Overflow [OV] indication. leandc will not update these when communication status of the station changes.

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" />
Table 3.9 IEC60870-5-101 Slave Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1...232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from the destination (e.g. downstream station) after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and negative response is sent to the upstream Master station. Application timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged, if communication to the destination (e.g. downstream station) is lost.
Command 1...232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance attempts to send command response to the upstream Master station. If it is not possible to send a response within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). Command timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged, if communication to the upstream Master station is lost.
Select 1...232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, object is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />
Table 3.10 IEC60870-5-101 Slave TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

TimeZone

 Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic AI="60" />
Table 3.11 IEC60870-5-101 Slave Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
AI 0...232 - 1 0 sec Periodic analogue value reporting interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic analog value reporting.

BufferSizes

Communication and event buffer sizes can be specified in this node.

Please see sample BufferSizes node and all its attributes in the table below.

<BufferSizes DIEVmult="1.1" AIEVmult="2.1" ASDUTx="253" />
Table 3.12 IEC60870-5-101 Slave BufferSizes attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

DIEVmult

 2...32 4 DI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of DI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of DI objects)

AIEVmult

 2...32 4 AI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of AI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of AI objects)
ASDUTx 14...253 253 bytes Application layer transmission buffer size in bytes. Maximal length of message transmitted over IEC60870-5-101 communication link is 255 bytes. Including the link layer framing, maximal size of the application layer is 253 bytes (if LinkAddrSize is 1 byte) or 252 (if LinkAddrSize is 2 bytes). This attribute is used to limit maximal length of a transmitted message.

4. IEC60870-5-104 Slave

This section describes how to configure IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance must have XML configuration file where its IO object table and additional protocol-related settings will be stored. One and the same XML configuration file can be used for multiple IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances, this becomes useful in case if identical IO objects need to be reported to several Master stations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC104sl_test.xml‘ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC104sl.XMLpath attribute of a communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC104sl_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-104 Slave configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC104sl_test.xml’) must have a root object node IEC104slConfig which has 6 child group object nodes VersionControl; ProtocolCfg; DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable please see the sample below.

<IEC104slConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC104sl" … version="1.00">
   <VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
   <ProtocolCfg>
      <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
      <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
      …
   </ProtocolCfg>
   <DITable>
      <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10"/>
      …
   </DITable>
   <AITable>
      <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="10" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0"/>
      …
   </AITable>
   <DOTable>
      <DO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
      …
   </DOTable>
   <AOTable>
      <AO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
      …
   </AOTable>
</IEC104slConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable group nodes compose an IO object table and they are common for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances. Please refer to the tables 5.1; 5.6; 5.10 and 5.14 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group node

ProtocolCfg group and its child element nodes contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg node and all available child element nodes below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element node.

<ProtocolCfg>
   <XMLSettings … />
   <TransportSettings … />
   <CommsSettings … />
   <ASDUSettings … />
   <ServiceSettings … />
   <Timeouts … />
   <TimeSettings … />
   <Periodic … />
   <BufferSizes … />
   <Miscellaneous … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 4.1 IEC60870-5-104 Slave XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

TransportSettings

Protocol transport interface settings such as timeout and message window sizes can be specified using attributes of TransportSettings element node.

Please see sample TransportSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TransportSettings T1="15" T2="10" T3="20" Kparam="12" Wparam="8" />
Table 4.2 IEC60870-5-104 Slave TransportSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
T1 1...65535 15 sec Timeout of send or test APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance waits a reply to a sent APDU [I-frame] or test message [TESTFR_act]. If no reply is received from peer station within a configured timeout, communication protocol instance initiates active close of the TCP socket.
T2 1...65535 10 sec Timeout for acknowledges in case of no data messages as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. (requirement: T2timer < T1timer) It is a delay in seconds before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame] in case there are any unacknowledged messages from the peer station.
T3 1...65535 20 sec Timeout for sending test messages in case of a long idle state from IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a maximal idle time in seconds before a test message [TESTFR_act] is sent to a peer station by the communication protocol instance. If this timeout is selected greater than T3 timeout configured in the peer station, it is most likely the test message will be sent by the peer station first.
Kparam 1...30 12 APDU Maximum difference receive sequence number to send state variable as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Maximal number of outgoing APDU messages [I-frame] communication protocol instance will send to a peer station before it waits for an acknowledge [S-frame]
Wparam 1...29 8 APDU Latest acknowledge after receiving w number I format APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Number of incoming APDU messages [I-frame] received from a peer station before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame]

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and the table listing all available attributes below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10" StartupGIDelay="10" />

Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 1...232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before status of this protocol instance is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated after TCP socket has been closed. Default 0 seconds - station status will change to OFFLINE immediately after TCP socket has been closed by a remote host.
StartupGIDelay 0...232 - 1 0 sec Incoming General interrogation commands are rejected for a configured number of seconds on leandc startup. Negative confirmation will be sent to General Interrogation requests received before the delay expires. This delay allows leandc to poll data from outstations for the first time on startup, before data is being requested by an upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings InvalidEvent="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" DIEventType="31" AIEventType="36" DOType="46" AOType="50" DIInterDelay="8000" DIIndetDelay="3500" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" TimeSync="1" TranspTypes="1" ForwardGI="1" CommandLatency="300" />
Table 4.4 IEC60870-5-104 Slave ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will be set (‘1’) to indicate last hour of the Summer Time before a clock adjustment at the end of the Daylight Saving Time (DST) (this is when clock is turned back one hour)
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will always be set (‘1’) if the date and time of the tag is Summer Time. Please note this functionality is deviation from communication standard and option should be avoided.
DIEventType See table 5.3 30 [M_SP_TB_1] Use this ASDU type to send DI events which don’t have DI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 30 – ‘Single-point Information’, DI event will be sent using ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time)
AIEventType See table 5.8 36 [M_ME_TF_1] Use this ASDU type to send AI events which don’t have AI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 36 – ‘Short floating point’, AI event will be sent using ASDU type 36 [M_ME_TF_1], CP56time2A, full time)
DOType See table 5.12 0 = any Only accept command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Single or Double command) if DO object doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
AOType See table 5.16 0 = any Only accept setpoint command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Normalized or Scaled setpoint) if AO object doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
DOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if DO object doesn’t have DO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
AOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if AO object doesn’t have AO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
DIInterDelay 0...232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.InterDelay attribute. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds)
DIIndetDelay 0...232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.IndetDelay attribute. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds)
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after system leandc
TimeSync 0 0 Reject incoming clock synchronization messages.
1 Accept incoming clock synchronization messages and synchronize internal real time clock. Please note internal real time clock will be synchronized immediately if a time difference between received time stamp and the internal clock is greater than 1 hour. If a time difference is less than 1 hour, internal clock will be adjusted only once an hour.

TranspTypes

 0 0 ASDU type of every DI/AI object is determined by XML configuration settings.
1 ASDU type of every DI/AI object will be made transparent whenever possible. The same ASDU type will be used to report DI/AI object to upstream station as received from downstream outstation, providing both source and destination communication protocol instances are compatible. Otherwise default ASDU type will be used. Please note object will be excluded from General Interrogation response before it is received from downstream outstation on leandc startup. This is because it is impossible to determine ASDU type of the object before is has been received from outstation.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
CommandLatency 0...232 - 1 0 sec Maximal difference in seconds between received time-tagged control command and the internal time. If this attribute is used, time-tag of the received control command is checked and command will be discarded if it has been substantially delayed. Value 0 disables time-tagged command validation and any incoming control command will be accepted.

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control quality flags of the DI/AI events generated when outstation goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings NotInitFlags="0x80" DisabledFlags="0x80" OfflineFlags="0x40" PostOfflineFlags="0x80" EventMask="0x00" />
Table 4.5 IEC60870-5-104 Slave ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NotInitFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. See table 4.7 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires on leandc startup. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
DisabledFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station gets Disabled with a Service command. See table 4.7 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station gets Disabled. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
OfflineFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station state changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires) See table 4.7 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when OfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
PostOfflineFlags 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers after PostOfflineDelay timer expires. See table 4.7 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when PostOfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
EventMask 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See table 4.6 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 4.6 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
Bits 4...7 Any Bits reserved for future use
Table 4.7 DI/AI qualifier quality bits
Bits Value Description
Quality bits [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DI/AI qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will not be set
xxx1.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will be set
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will not be set
xx1x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will be set
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will not be set
x1xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will be set
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will not be set
1xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will be set
Bits 0...3 xxxx.0000 Bits are used for Single/Double status information and Overflow [OV] indication. leandc will not update these when communication status of the station changes.

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" />
Table 4.8 IEC60870-5-104 Slave Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1...232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from the destination (e.g. downstream station) after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and negative response is sent to the upstream Master station. Application timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged, if communication to the destination (e.g. downstream station) is lost.
Command 1...232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance attempts to send command response to the upstream Master station. If it is not possible to send a response within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). Command timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged, if communication to the upstream Master station is lost.
Select 1...232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, object is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />
Table 4.9 IEC60870-5-104 Slave TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

TimeZone

 Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic AI="60" />

Attribute Values or range Default Description

BufferSizes

Communication buffer sizes can be specified in this node.

Please see sample BufferSizes node and all its attributes in the table below.

<BufferSizes DIEVmult="1.1" AIEVmult="2.1" />
Table 4.11 IEC60870-5-104 Slave BufferSizes attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

DIEVmult

 2...32 4 DI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of DI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of DI objects)

AIEVmult

 2...32 4 AI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of AI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of AI objects)

Miscellaneous

Miscellaneous and project-specific settings can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Miscellaneous node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Miscellaneous LegacyAIEVinitdelay="2" />
Table 4.12 IEC60870-5-104 Slave Miscellaneous attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
LegacyAIEVinitdelay 0...232 - 1 0 sec Attribute enables specially marked (legacy spontaneous-only) AI object initialization after configured number of seconds on leandc startup. Feature applies only to AI objects that have Legacy bit [2] set in AI.qualifier . Legacy AI objects will be reported spontaneously with a last known value from the internal database whenever downstream outstation goes online e.g. after a communication loss or when Enabled with a Service command. In this case AI events will not have either Invalid [IV] nor Not Topical [NT] bits set, with the exception on leandc startup. AI events will have value 0 and Invalid bit [IV] set when initialized for the first time on leandc startup. This functionality is not affected by the use of the LegacyAIEVinitdelay attribute and applies always if a particular AI object has Legacy bit [2] set in AI.qualifier . LegacyAIEVinitdelay attribute extends functionality by providing a mechanism to remove Invalid [IV] bit after configured number of seconds. (The Invalid [IV] bit was set when legacy AI events had been sent to the upstream station for the first time on leandc startup.) AI objects with 0 value and cleared Invalid [IV] bit will be sent using Background scan message(s) after number of seconds configured in LegacyAIEVinitdelay attribute. This ensures upstream station (e.g. SCADA) will have a valid legacy AI object with 0 value in the database. As a result upstream station will be ready to process first genuine AI event when it arrives.

5. IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave IO table

This section describes how to configure IO object table for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance. Group object nodes DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable are included in XML configuration files of the IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances as described in previous sections IEC60870-5-101 Slave and IEC60870-5-104 Slave.

DITable group and DI node

Group node DITable and child element nodes DI are used to create DI information objects to send static status information and status change events to the upstream Master station. Each created DI information object needs to have a source of information. The source is created by linking DI information object to a DI node of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using DI.Device and DI.Index attributes. The first step is to select the source Master protocol instance, use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance. The next step is to select the source DI object, use value of the DI.Index attribute of any DI object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance. Enter the selected values of source Master protocol instance in DI.Device attribute and source DI object in DI.Index attribute.

Information address (IOA) to send DI information object upstream is specified in InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample DITable group and DI child element nodes below. There are 5 DI information objects configured using 4 DI nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0" GroupMask="0x0001" … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x10" TypeID="30"  … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="-2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x00" TypeID="30"  … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Total="2" … />
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0" GroupMask="0x0001" TypeID="30" OffIndex="5" InterDelay="8000" IndetDelay="3500" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 5.1 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Device

 1...254 n/a Source communication protocol instance. Any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group can be used as a source. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as a source for this DI object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.

Index

 -8...232 - 8 n/a Source DI object. Any DI element node of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a source. Use value of the DI.Index attribute of any DI object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. In addition to regular DIs there are internal indications available. Internal indications are used to monitor real-time status of the source protocol instance. Each internal indication has a service index and they are summarized in the table 5.4. Indexes don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

InfAddr

 1...16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the DI object. This IOA will be used to send object to upstream station. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 5.2 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

GroupMask

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0x0000 Include object in Interrogation group/groups. Each bit of the group mask attribute needs to be set in order to include object in a particular interrogation group. Please refer to the table 5.9 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

TypeID

 See table 5.3 2 [M_SP_TA_1] or 30 [M_SP_TB_1] Use this ASDU Type to send a DI event. Attribute also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) being reported to General interrogation request. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

OffIndex

 -8...232 - 8 Same as Index DI object index of the second single point used as a source for conversion to double status indication. Resulting Double point will have ON value when source DI object specified in Index attribute is ON. Resulting Double point will have OFF value when source DI object specified in OffIndex attribute is ON. See table 5.5 for additional information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, no conversion will take place if this attribute is omitted.

InterDelay

 0...232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double point objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

IndetDelay

 0...232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double point objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Total

 1...16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.qualifier

Table 5.2 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation enabled. An OFF event will be internally generated following every sent DI ON event. DI object will always have OFF value in Interrogation responses.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI events enabled. DI event will be sent upstream if state of the object changes or new event is received from the source communication protocol instance
xxxx.x1xx DI events disabled
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI object will be included in General Interrogation response
xxxx.1xxx DI object will be excluded from General Interrogation response
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event when 2 Single Point objects are merged into a Double Point object. e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used for resulting DPI.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event when 2 Single Point objects are merged into a Double Point object. e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used for resulting DPI.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx All DI events will be sent upstream
x1xx.xxxx DI events with OFF values or with set [IV] bit will be discarded. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be sent upstream
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will not be sent upstream
Bit 4 Any Bits reserved for future use

DI.TypeID

Table 5.3 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI TypeID
TypeID Value for IEC60870-5-101 TypeID Value for IEC60870-5-104 Description
1 1 Static DI ‘Single-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1], no time-tag
2 N/A Static DI ‘Single-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
3 3 Static DI ‘Double-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1], no time-tag
4 N/A Static DI ‘Double-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 4 [M_DP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
30 30 Static DI ‘Single-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
31 31 Static DI ‘Double-point Information’ will be sent using ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1] DI event will be sent using ASDU type 31 [M_DP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
Other Other Undefined, default values will be used: IEC60870-5-101 default ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min IEC60870-5-104 default ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time

Tip

Note, all DI objects are internally stored and processed as ‘Double-point status information’. If ‘Single-point status information’ type needs to be reported to the upstream Master station, object is being converted just before it is sent.

DI Service Indexes

Service digital inputs are internal indications that provide real-time status information of communication protocol instances. Service indications have negative index values and can be used just as any regular DI indexes.

Table 5.4 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave Service DI indexes
Index value Object value Description
-2 (0xFFFFFFFE) ON Communication between leandc and peer station is running, peer station is Online. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
OFF Communication between leandc and peer station is lost, peer station is Offline. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
-3 (0xFFFFFFFD) ON Communication between leandc and peer station is Enabled. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
OFF Communication between leandc and peer station is Disabled. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
-4* (0xFFFFFFFC) ON Communication to peer station is Started. Refer to the comment below for the list of protocol instances that provide this service indication.
OFF Communication to peer station is Stopped. Refer to the comment below for the list of protocol instances that provide this service indication.
-5 (0xFFFFFFFB) ON Only used for protocol instances linked to UART hardware node; State of the UART Ring Indicator RI pin(9) is active (+12V). This service DI can be used only if UART.CtrlRdTimer attribute is defined.
OFF Only used for protocol instances linked to UART hardware node; State of the UART Ring Indicator RI pin(9) is not active (-12V). This service DI can be used only if UART.CtrlRdTimer attribute is defined.
-1 and -6...-8 Any Internal indications reserved for future use

Tip

* This service indication only applies to the following protocol instances:
IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication is [Started] or [Stopped]. ON ([Started] state) indicates [STARTDT_con] has been received from outstation;
IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication is [Started] or [Stopped]. ON ([Started] state) indicates [STARTDT_act] message has been received from upstream station;
IEC61850 Client association state. ON indicates associated state i.e. [Initiate-ResponsePDU] message has been received from IED;

DI SPI/DPI conversion

Single to double point conversion takes place if OffIndex attribute is used. Values of source DI objects and resulting DPI object are listed in the truth table below.

Table 5.5 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave SPI/DPI truth table
Value of Index DI Value of OffIndex DI Resulting DPI
OFF (0) OFF (0) Intermediate (0)
OFF (0) ON (1) OFF (1)
ON (1) OFF (0) ON (2)
ON (1) ON (1) Indeterminate (error) (3)
Other Other Indeterminate (error) (3)

Intermediate and Indeterminate state reporting can be delayed using InterDelay and IndetDelay attributes respectively. If ON->INTER->OFF or OFF->INTER->ON transition successfully completes before InterDelay timer expiration, Intermediate state will not be reported. Delay setting has to be carefully selected to ensure it always exceeds time required for ON->INTER->OFF or OFF->INTER->ON transitions to complete, to take advantage of this functionality. If delay attributes are set 0 Intermediate and Indeterminate states will be reported as soon as values of source DI objects become those listed in the table above.

AITable group and AI node

Group node AITable and child element nodes AI are used to create AI information objects to send static analogue values and analog events to the upstream Master station. Each created AI information object needs to have a source of information. The source is created by linking AI information object to an AI node of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using AI.Device and AI.Index attributes. The first step is to select the source Master protocol instance, use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance. The next step is to select the source AI object, use value of the AI.Index attribute of any AI object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance. Enter the selected values of source Master protocol instance in AI.Device attribute and source AI object in AI.Index attribute.

Information address (IOA) to send AI information object upstream is specified in InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample AITable group and AI child element nodes below. There are 5 AI information objects configured using 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Offset="28.0" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x00" ZeroDeadband="1.0" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x01" Coeff="0.05" GroupMask="0x0002" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="3" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0" Offset="2.0" Total="2" … />
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0" Coeff="100.0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="5.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" GroupMask="0x0002" TypeID="13" Total="2" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 5.6 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Device

 1...254 n/a Source communication protocol instance. Any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group can be used as a source. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as a source for this AI object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.

Index

 0...232 - 1 n/a Source AI object. Any AI element node of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a source. Use value of the AI.Index attribute of any AI object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. Indexes don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

InfAddr

 1...16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the AI object. This IOA will be used to send object to upstream station. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 5.7 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Coeff

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the analog object value before sending to upstream Master station. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

StartOffset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ZeroDeadband

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Offset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

OffsetDeadband

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

NonZeroOffset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

GroupMask

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0x0000 Include object in Interrogation group/groups. Each bit of the group mask attribute needs to be set in order to include object in a particular interrogation group. Please refer to the table 5.9 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

TypeID

 See table 5.8 14 [M_ME_TC_1] or 36 [M_ME_TF_1] Use this ASDU Type to send a AI event. Attribute also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point value) being reported to General interrogation request Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Total

 1...16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling and application examples using StartOffset ; ZeroDeadband ; Offset ; OffsetDeadband ; NonZeroOffset attributes.

AI.qualifier

Table 5.7 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave AI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation enabled. A value 0 event will be internally generated following every sent AI event sent with nonzero value. AI object will always have 0 value in interrogation responses.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx AI events enabled. AI event will be sent upstream if event is received from the source communication protocol instance
xxxx.x1xx AI events disabled
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx AI object will be included in General Interrogation response
xxxx.1xxx AI object will be excluded from General Interrogation response
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Send AI events upstream with their original value and use the same value for Interrogation response and periodic reporting
x1xx.xxxx Send AI events upstream with their original value, but use value 0 for Interrogation response and periodic reporting
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be sent upstream
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will not be sent upstream
Bits 0;4;5 Any Bits reserved for future use

Tip

Note, all AI objects are internally stored and processed as ‘Short floating point’ values. If any other type needs to be reported to the upstream Master station, object is being converted just before it is sent.
