9. IEC60870-5-103 Master

This section describes how to configure IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance must have XML configuration file where its IO object table and additional protocol-related settings will be stored. One and the same XML configuration file can be used for multiple IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instances, this becomes useful in case if identical sets of IO objects are acquired from several outstations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC103ma_test.xml‘ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC103ma.XMLpath attribute of a communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC103ma_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-103 Master configuration file (e.g. ‘“IEC103ma_test.xml‘) must have a root object node IEC103maConfig which has 5 child group object nodes VersionControl; ProtocolCfg; DITable; AITable; DOTable please see the sample below.

<IEC103maConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC103ma" … version="1.00">
   <VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
   <ProtocolCfg>
      <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
      <ASDUSettings SUthroughoutDST="1" />
      …
   </ProtocolCfg>
   <DITable>
      <DI Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="240" INF="160"/>
      …
   </DITable>
   <AITable>
      <AI Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="134" INF="148" MEA="0" Coeff="0.09" Percent="0.1"/>
      …
   </AITable>
   <DOTable>
      <DO Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="240" INF="160" TypeID="0"/>
      …
   </DOTable>
</IEC103maConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable group nodes compose an IO object table of the IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables 9.11; 9.13 and 9.15 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group node

ProtocolCfg group and its child element nodes contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg node and all available child element nodes below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element node.

<ProtocolCfg>
   <LinkSettings … />
   <CommsSettings … />
   <ASDUSettings … />
   <ServiceSettings … />
   <Timeouts … />
   <TimeSettings … />
   <Broadcast … />
   <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings Flags="0x00"/>
Table 9.1 IEC60870-5-103 Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Flags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See table 9.2 for description.
Table 9.2 IEC60870-5-103 Master Link flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Link flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send variable and fixed length link layer messages as required. (First character of variable link layer message is - 0x68 and fixed length message - 0x10)
xxxx.xxx1 Send only variable length link layer messages
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Use ‘Reset of remote link’ message to check if station is online. ([Reset of remote link] message has function code 0x40)
xxx1.xxxx Use ‘Reset FCB’ message to check if station is online. ([Reset FCB] message has function code 0x47. This message is defined only in IEC60870-5-103 standard)
Bits 1...3;5...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" ControlLockTimer="20" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" OnlineGIDelay="10" />
Table 9.3 IEC60870-5-103 Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

NoRespCount

 1...255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)

DegradedRetries

 0...255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.

DegradedTimeout

 0...232 - 1 600 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.

ControlLockTimer

 0...120 20 sec Control command lock timer is used to poll only one outstation for a configured number of seconds after sending a control command. All other outstations that share the same hardware channel (e.g. serial port) are temporary excluded from polling while ControlLockTimer operates. This feature enables to speed up reception of a control command feedback. ControlLockTimer can only be used if more than one outstation share the hardware channel. Value 0 disables control lock timer feature.

OfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay

PostOfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)

OnlineGIDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec General Interrogation command will be delayed for a configured number of seconds after outstation comes online. Delay is designed to allow outstation to poll data after reset/power-on and before data is requested by leandc with a General Interrogation command.

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings InvalidEvent="1" IgnoreTimetags="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1" />
Table 9.4 IEC60870-5-103 Master ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no threshold, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will be set (‘1’) to indicate last hour of the Summer Time before a clock adjustment at the end of the Daylight Saving Time (DST) (this is when clock is turned back one hour)
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of any outgoing message will always be set (‘1’) if the date and time of the tag is Summer Time. Please note this functionality is deviation from communication standard and option should be avoided.

AIDeadband

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature

AIPercent

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after system leandc
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 9.5 IEC60870-5-103 Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See table 9.6 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 9.6 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
Bits 4...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" />
Table 9.7 IEC60870-5-103 Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1...232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1...232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />
Table 9.8 IEC60870-5-103 Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

TimeZone

 Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

Broadcast

Broadcast common address of ASDU (CAA) usage for various commands can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Broadcast node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Broadcast GI="1" TimeSync="0" />
Table 9.9 IEC60870-5-103 Master Broadcast attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

GI

 0 0 Send General Interrogation commands with individual Common Addresses of ASDU (CAA)
1 Send General Interrogation commands with broadcast Common Address of ASDU (CAA). Broadcast address is 255

TimeSync

 0 0 Send Time Synchronization [C_CS_NA_1] commands with individual link and Common Addresses of ASDU (CAA)
1 Send Time Synchronization [C_CS_NA_1] commands with broadcast link and Common Address of ASDU (CAA). Broadcast address is 255

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic GI="600" TimeSync="0" />
Table 9.10 IEC60870-5-103 Master Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
GI 0...232 - 1 0 sec Periodic General Interrogation command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic General Interrogation command.
TimeSync 0...232 - 1 0 sec Periodic Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic time synchronization command. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.

DITable group and DI node

Group node DITable and child element nodes DI are used to create DI information objects to receive status information from the downstream outstation. Each created DI information object can be used as source of information for any DI information object defined in IO table of the Slave protocol instances. If used as a source, status information received from an outstation will be forwarded to DI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section DITable group and DI node for more information on how to use DI information object as a source.

In order to receive a status information from downstream outstation [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes.

Please see sample DITable group and DI child element nodes below. There are 5 DI information objects configured using 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00"/>
     <DI Index="1" FUN="1" INF="2" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DI Index="2" FUN="240" INF="55" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DI Index="3" FUN="240" INF="56" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0" InterDelay="10000" IndetDelay="0" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 9.11 IEC60870-5-103 Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.

FUN

 0...255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the DI object. This FUN will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

INF

 0...255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the DI object. This INF will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 9.12 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

InterDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate state of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate state) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

IndetDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) state) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Total

 1...254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and INF values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.Qualifier

Table 9.12 IEC60870-5-103 Master DI internal Qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3)
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation enabled. An OFF event will be internally generated following every sent DI ON event. Static DI object will be set to OFF value, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated only if a DI object state has changed
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time DI object is received from outstation. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this DI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 3;4;6 Any Bits reserved for future use

AITable group and AI node

Group node AITable and child element nodes AI are used to create AI information objects to receive analog information from the downstream outstation. Each created AI information object can be used as source of information for any AI information object defined in IO table of the Slave protocol instances. If used as a source, analog information received from an outstation will be forwarded to AI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section AITable group and AI node for more information on how to use AI information object as a source.

In order to receive an analog information from downstream outstation [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes. It also essential to select particular measurement from the incoming message as IEC60870-5-103 station sends multiple measurands in one message. Particular analog value is selected with MEA attribute.

Please see sample AITable group and AI child element nodes below. There are 5 AI information objects configured using 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" FUN="1" INF="1" MEA="5" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="2" FUN="85" INF="83" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="-17.0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="3" FUN="105" INF="103" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="0.08" Total="2"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" FUN="85" INF="83" MEA="2" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" DIAndIndex="0" LogicValue="1" Total="2" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 9.13 IEC60870-5-103 Master AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.

FUN

 0...255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the AI object. This FUN will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

INF

 0...255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the AI object. This INF will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

MEA

 0...31 n/a Number of the analog value in the received measurement message. Use value 0 to select first measurement in the received message. Numbers don’t have to be arranged in an ascending order.

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 9.14 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Coeff

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Deadband

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from the analog value stored in the database in order to create absolute deadband range (range is: ‘oldvalue - deadband’ … ‘oldvalue + deadband’). New incoming analog value is checked against limits of this deadband and an event is generated if value is outside. Value 0 disables deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

Percent

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate absolute deadband based on the last analog value stored in the database. When absolute deadband range is calculated, the same procedure as described above applies. Value 0 disables percent deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

StartOffset

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ZeroDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Offset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

OffsetDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

NonZeroOffset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

DIAndIndex

 0...65534 n/a Index of the DI object to perform logical conjunction (AND function). Use value of the DI.Index attribute. Analog value will be stored in the database and event will be generated only if value of the DI object is the same as specified in LogicValue attribute. Attribute is optional and must not be specified in configuration if not used. There is no default value.

LogicValue

 0...255 0 Value of the object used for logical conjunction/disjunction (AND/OR function). Please note all DI values have to be treated as DPIs (ON = 2; OFF = 1) if used for logic functions. Quality flags (e.g. [IV]) are not part of the logical processing, DI values are used regardless of state of the quality flags. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Total

 1...254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and MEA values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

AI.Qualifier

Table 9.14 IEC60870-5-103 Master AI internal Qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x
Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation enabled. New 0 value event will be generated internally following every:
/ event with a nonzero value received from outstation and
/ event with a nonzero value resulted from a deadband/percent or scaling processing.
Static AI object will be set to value 0, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated if an AI object is received from outstation with a ‘spontaneous’ Cause Of Transmission ([COT] = 1) or received value exceeds deadband/percent limit.
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time AI object is received from outstation regardless of the Cause Of Transmission. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this AI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original AI value and store original value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
x1xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original value, but store 0 value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 0;3;4;5 Any Bits reserved for future use

DOTable group and DO node

Group node DOTable and child element nodes DO are used to create DO information objects to send control command to the downstream outstation. Each created DO information object can be used as a destination for any DO information object defined in IO table of the Slave protocol instances. If used as a destination, procedure is as follows: Slave protocol instance receives control command from the upstream Master station and forwards to destination DO information object. Then current communication protocol instance prepares and sends command to the outstation based on DO information object settings. Please refer to the section DOTable for more information on how to use DO information object as a destination.

In order to send a control command to downstream outstation [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO child element nodes below. There are 5 DO information objects configured using 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00"/>
     <DO Index="1" FUN="1" INF="2" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DO Index="2" FUN="240" INF="55" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DO Index="3" FUN="240" INF="56" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DO attributes

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DO object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.

 0...255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the DO object. This FUN will be used to send command to downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

INF

 0...255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the DO object. This INF will be used to send command to downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.

Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and INF values without a need to create a DO node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

xxxx.xxx1 DO object will be inverted (OFF → ON; ON → OFF)

10. Modbus Master

This section describes how to configure Modbus RTU/ASCII/TCP Master communication protocol instance. Each Modbus Master communication protocol instance must have XML configuration file where Modbus messages, IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple Modbus Master communication protocol instances. It becomes very useful if multiple outstations have identical sets of IO objects.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘Device_IO.xml‘ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in Modbusma.XMLpath attribute of a communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”Device_IO.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

Modbus Master configuration file (e.g. ‘Device_IO.xml‘) must have a root object node ModbusmaConfig which has 2 mandatory child group object nodes VersionControl; ProtocolCfg, 3 optional message configuration nodes InitMessages; PollMessages; CtrlMessages and 3 optional child group object nodes DITable; AITable; DOTable. Please see the sample below.

<ModbusmaConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/Modbusma" … version="1.00">
   <VersionControl conf="2.00" date="2018-03-19" time="12:00:09"/>
   <ProtocolCfg>
      <LinkSettings Type="RTU" />
      <CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="3" DegradedTimeout="60" OfflineDelay="10" />
      <Hardcoded Type="BCAIIS8" />
      …
   </ProtocolCfg>
   <InitMessages>
      <MSG InitMsg="1" Func="17" Data="0x00"/>
      …
   </InitMessages>
   <PollMessages>
      <MSG PollMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0002" Count="1"/>
      …
   </PollMessages>
   <CtrlMessages>
      <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x000A" Data="0x0000"/>
      …
   </CtrlMessages>
   <DITable>
      <DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" Total="2"/>
      …
   </DITable>
   <AITable>
      <AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Coeff="0.09" Deadband="0.1"/>
      …
   </AITable>
   <DOTable>
      <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0"/>
      …
   </DOTable>
</ModbusmaConfig>

InitMessages; PollMessages; CtrlMessages group nodes contain Modbus messages used for communication to outstation. Messages don’t have to be defined if any of Hardcoded device types is specified.

DITable; AITable; DOTable group nodes make up an IO object table of the Modbus Master communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables 10.21; 10.25 and 10.29 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group node

ProtocolCfg group and its child element nodes contain protocol-related settings of the Modbus Master instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg node and all available child element nodes below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element node.

<ProtocolCfg>
       <LinkSettings … />
       <CommsSettings … />
       <Hardcoded … />
       <AppSettings … />
       <ServiceSettings … />
       <Timeouts … />
       <TimeSettings … />
       <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings Frame="RTU" />
Table 10.1 Modbus Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Frame

 RTU* RTU Frame format of the Modbus messages. Please note frame format of all protocol instances sharing the hardware node must be the same.

Important

* Only Modbus® RTU frame format is available in the current release of leandc firmware, more formats to be added in the future.

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" />
Table 10.2 Modbus Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

NoRespCount

 1...255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)

DegradedRetries

 0...255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.

DegradedTimeout

 0...232 - 1 600 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.

OfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay

PostOfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)

Hardcoded

Hardcoded device type can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Hardcoded node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Hardcoded Type="BCDI16" />

Attribute Values or range Default Description

Type

 See table 10.4 n/a Predefined type of a Modbus device. Messages and communication sequences are hardcoded for these devices. Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the device type when specifying.

Type Description
BCDI16 Brainchild Digital Input (16) module DI16. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=16, AI=0, DO=0, AO=0
BCAIIS8 Brainchild isolated Analog Input (8) module AIIS8. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=0, AI=8, DO=0, AO=0
LEDOM16 Londelec Digital Output (16) module DOM16. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=0, AI=0, DO=16, AO=0
LEIODC-C32-3100 Londelec LEIODC-C32-3100 unit. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=12, AI=0, DO=4, AO=0
LEIODC-X32-3100 Londelec LEIODC-X32-3100 unit. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=12, AI=0, DO=4, AO=0
LEIODC-X10-3100 Londelec LEIODC-X10-3100 unit. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=12, AI=0, DO=4, AO=0
LEIODC-X32-4000 Londelec LEIODC-X32-4000 unit. Data points are automatically created for this device as follows: DI=16, AI=0, DO=0, AO=0

Other Undefined, none of hardcoded device types will be used

AppSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of AppSettings element node.

Please see sample AppSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AppSettings AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" />
Table 10.5 Modbus Master AppSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

AIDeadband

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature

AIPercent

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 10.6 Modbus Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See table 10.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 10.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
Bits 4...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Timeout values can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" t35="0.01" />
Table 10.8 Modbus Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1...232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1...232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.

t35

 0.00001...42949 0.01 sec Receive line idle detection timer (t3.5 in the communication standard). Incoming message analyze begins when idle in the receive line exceeds configured number of seconds.

TimeSettings

Time settings node is used to construct a message for synchronizing Modbus device’s clock. Modbus communication standard doesn’t define a specific function for the purpose of time synchronization, Write Multiple registers [16] is normally used. However encoding of the date and time in Modbus registers varies greatly from one device to another. Attributes of the TimeSettings node below enable to build a custom Modbus message where date and time values can be placed in any registers and each formatted in a different way.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings Func="0x10" Reg="0xAA55" Count="8" YearType="97" MonType="33" DomType="33" DowType="0" HourType="33" MinType="33" SecType="33" YearBitOffset="48" MonBitOffset="32" DomBitOffset="40" DowBitOffset="0" HourBitOffset="16" MinBitOffset="24" SecBitOffset="0"/>
Table 10.9 Modbus Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Func

 16 [Preset Multiple Registers] n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.

Reg

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to this register.

Count

 0...63 1 Number of Modbus registers to write to outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

YearType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the year number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means year will be excluded from the message.

MonType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the month number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means month will be excluded from the message.

DomType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the day of month number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means day of month will be excluded from the message.

DowType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the day of week number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means day of week will be excluded from the message.

HourType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the hour number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means hour will be excluded from the message.

MinType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the minute number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means minute will be excluded from the message.

SecType

 See table 10.11 0 Format of the second number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means second will be excluded from the message.

YearBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the year number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

MonBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the month number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

DomBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the day of month number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

DowBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the day of week number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

HourBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the hour number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

MinBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the minute number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

SecBitOffset

 0...1023 or 0x00...0x3FF 0 Shift the second number left by the specified number of bits. See table 10.10 for examples.

Table below shows position of a sample value ‘85’ (0x55) in a Modbus message depending on the BitOffset.

Table 10.10 Modbus Master Bit Offset sample values
BitOffset Modbus Message
0 {01 10 ... 00 55 00 00 ...}
1 {01 10 ... 00 AA 00 00 ...}
2 {01 10 ... 01 54 00 00 ...}
3 {01 10 ... 02 A8 00 00 ...}
4 {01 10 ... 05 50 00 00 ...}
8 {01 10 ... 55 00 00 00 ...}
16 {01 10 ... 00 00 00 55 ...}
24 {01 10 ... 00 00 55 00 ...}
Table 10.11 Modbus Master Time variable encoding types
Type value Description
0 Value is not used
33 Encode value as 16bit Unsigned Integer big endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 ... 07 E2 ...}
35 Encode value as 16bit Unsigned Integer little endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 ... E2 07 ...}
97 Encode value as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) big endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 ... 20 18 ...}
98 Encode value as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) little endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 ... 18 20 ...}
Other Value is not used

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic TimeSync="0" />
Table 10.12 Modbus Master Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeSync 0...232 - 1 0 sec Periodic Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic time synchronization command. Time synchronization message must be defined in TimeSettings node. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.

InitMessages group and MSG node

Group node InitMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages that are being sent to outstation during an initialization stage. Outstation replies can be checked against the pre-defined data to ensure correct outstation is connected during the initialization stage. Modbus Write messages can be used to change settings of the outstation during the initialization stage, if necessary.

Tip

InitMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required for initialization of hardcoded devices are set-up automatically.

Please see sample InitMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<InitMessages>
     <MSG InitMsg="1" Func="17" Data="0x00"/>
     <MSG InitMsg="2" Func="4" Reg="0x0003" Count="1" Data="0x00" />
</InitMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG InitMsg="1" Func="4" Reg="0x0100" Count="1" Data="0xAA BB CC DD 05 03" Flags="0x00" Name="Read Input Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

MSG attributes

Table 10.13 Modbus Master Initialization message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

InitMsg

 1...65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.

Func

 See table 10.14 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.

Reg

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to or read from this register. See table 10.14 to check if Reg attribute is optional.

Count

 0...63 1 Number of Modbus registers to read from outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Data

 Up to 126 hexadecimal bytes 0x00...0xFF 0 Data to be written to outstation or expected in a reply from outstation. Data can be specified as hexadecimal values separated by whitespaces e.g. “AA BB CC DD 05 03” or a single hexadecimal number e.g. “0xAABBCCDD0503”. If writing / reading multiple Modbus registers first 2 data bytes will be written to / read from the base register specified in Reg attribute, next to 2 bytes base register + 1, etc.

Flags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Message flags to customize processing. See table 10.15 for available flags. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

MSG.Func

Table below shows supported values of the Func attribute and whether Reg attribute must be specified when particular Modbus function is used.

Table 10.14 Modbus Master Initialization message functions
Func Reg required Function Name
3 Yes [Read Holding Registers]
4 Yes [Read Input Registers]
5 Yes [Force Single Coil]
6 Yes [Preset Single Register]
16 Yes [Preset Multiple Registers]
17 No [Report Slave ID]
Other — Function is not supported

MSG.Flags

Table 10.15 Modbus Initialization message flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Message flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Data received from outstation has to match contents of the Data attribute exactly
xxxx.xxx1 Data received from outstation has to contain contents of the Data attribute. This option is normally used with Report Server ID [17] message and enables to check only portion of the received reply. For example if Data=”41 42 43” (represents string “ABC”) a reply from outstation {01 17 08 41 42 43 20 56 31 2E 30 ...} (represents string “ABC V1.0”) is considered valid.

PollMessages group and MSG node

Group node PollMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages that are being sent to continuously poll outstation data. All defined messages are sent to outstation in a sequential order. Data received from outstation can be mapped using DI and AI nodes.

Tip

PollMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required to poll data from a hardcoded device are set-up automatically.

Please see sample PollMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<PollMessages>
     <MSG PollMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0055" Count="2" />
     <MSG PollMsg="2" Func="4" Reg="0x0003" Count="1" />
</PollMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG PollMsg="1" Func="4" Reg="0x0100" Count="1" Name="Read Input Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

CtrlMessages group and MSG node

Group node CtrlMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages for writing data to outstation. Use DO node to specify which control message has to be sent to outstation when command is received.

Tip

CtrlMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required to send data to a hardcoded device are set-up automatically.

Please see sample CtrlMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0055" Type="1" />
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="16" Reg="0x0003" Data="0x0001" Type="0" />
</CtrlMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0100" Data="0x1122" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Type="0" Name="Write Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

MSG attributes

Table 10.18 Modbus Master Control message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

CtrlMsg

 1...65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.

Func

 See table 10.19 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.

Reg

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to or read from this register.

Data

 Up to 126 hexadecimal bytes 0x00...0xFF 0 Data to be written to outstation. Data can be specified as hexadecimal values separated by whitespaces e.g. “AA BB CC DD 05 03” or a single hexadecimal number e.g. “0xAABBCCDD0503”. If writing multiple Modbus registers first 2 data bytes will be written to the base register specified in Reg attribute, next to 2 bytes base register + 1, etc. See compatibility table 10.19 to check if Data attribute is optional.

Value 0 means this message does not follow any previous messages. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

MSG.Func

Table below shows supported values of the Func attribute and whether Data attribute must be specified when particular Modbus function is used.

Table 10.19 Modbus Master Control message functions
Func Type Data required Description
3 n/a No [Read Holding Registers] message will be sent and data received from outstation can be modified and used for the following write message. This message should be followed by a write message with Type=”1”.
4 n/a No [Read Input Registers] message will be sent and data received from outstation can be modified and used for the following write message. This message should be followed by a write message with Type=”1”.
5 0 Yes [Force Single Coil] message with contents of the Data attribute will be sent.
1 No [Force Single Coil] message will contain data received from outstation in a previous read message and the bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute will be set. If no read message is used, data is initialized to 0 and bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute is set.
6 0 Yes [Preset Single Register] message with contents of the Data attribute will be sent.
1 No [Preset Single Register] message will contain data received from outstation in a previous read message and the bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute will be set. If no read message is used, data is initialized to 0 and bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute is set.
16 0 Yes [Preset Multiple Registers] message with contents of the Data attribute will be sent.
1 No [Preset Multiple Registers] message will contain data received from outstation in a previous read message and the bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute will be set. If no read message is used, data is initialized to 0 and bit specified in DO.BitOffset attribute is set.
Other — — Function is not supported

MSG.Type

Table 10.20 Modbus Master Control message types
Type Description
0 Send contents of the MSG.Data attribute to outstation. DO.BitOffset attribute is ignored
1 Set only one bit as specified in DO.BitOffset attribute. MSG.Data attribute is ignored.
Other Not used

DITable group and DI node

Group node DITable and child element nodes DI are used to create information objects to receive status information from outstation. Each created DI can be used as a source for any DI information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Data received from outstation will be forwarded to the DI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section DITable group and DI node for more information on how to use DI information object as a source.

Tip

DITable group and DI nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. DI information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample DITable group and DI child element nodes below. There are 5 DI information objects configured using 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" />
     <DI Index="1" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="1" Type="1" />
     <DI Index="2" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="2" Type="1" Qualifier="0x01"/>
     <DI Index="3" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="4" Type="1" Total="2"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" Qualifier="0" ChatterFilter="100" Total="1" Name="Input 1" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

Table 10.21 Modbus Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.

PollMsg

 1...65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.PollMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 10.22 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ChatterFilter

 1...65535 50 msec Chatter filter in milliseconds for Digital Inputs. State change of the digital input will be reported only if remains stable for the period that exceeds configured filter. This attribute applies only to LEIODC series units.

Total

 1...254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and BitOffset values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

AITable group and AI node

Group node AITable and child element nodes AI are used to create AI information objects to receive analog information from outstation. Each created AI can be used as a source for any AI information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Analog data received from outstation will be forwarded to the AI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section AITable group and AI node for more information on how to use AI information object as a source.

Tip

AITable group and AI nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. AI information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample AITable group and AI child element nodes below. There are 5 AI information objects configured using 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="1" Type="33" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="2" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="2" Type="65" Coeff="-17.0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="3" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="4" Type="33" Coeff="0.08" Total="2"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" Total="1" Name="Voltage" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 10.25 Modbus Master AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.

PollMsg

 1...65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.PollMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.

RegOffset

 0...63 or 0x00...0x3F 0 Offset of the register to read the analog information from. See table 10.28 for examples of offset values. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.

Type

 See table 10.27 33 Select format of the received data. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 10.26 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Coeff

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Deadband

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from the analog value stored in the database in order to create absolute deadband range (range is: ‘oldvalue - deadband’ … ‘oldvalue + deadband’). New incoming analog value is checked against limits of this deadband and an event is generated if value is outside. Value 0 disables deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

Percent

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate absolute deadband based on the last analog value stored in the database. When absolute deadband range is calculated, the same procedure as described above applies. Value 0 disables percent deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

StartOffset

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ZeroDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Offset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

OffsetDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

NonZeroOffset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Total

 1...254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and RegOffset values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 0..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

AI.Type

Table 10.27 Modbus Master AI decode types
Type value Description
0 Not used
33 Decode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... FF 11 ...} will be decoded as ‘65297’
34 Decode data as 16bit Signed Integer big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... FF 11 ...} will be decoded as ‘-239’
35 Decode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 11 FF ...} will be decoded as ‘65297’
36 Decode data as 16bit Signed Integer little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 11 FF ...} will be decoded as ‘-239’
37 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [3210]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 00 01 00 05 ...} will be decoded as ‘65541’
38 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [1032]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 00 01 00 05 ...} will be decoded as ‘327681’
39 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [2301]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 00 01 00 05 ...} will be decoded as ‘16778496’
40 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [0123]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 00 01 00 05 ...} will be decoded as ‘83886336’
65 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [3210]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 40 00 10 80 ...} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
66 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [1032]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 10 80 40 00 ...} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
67 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [2301]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 00 40 80 10 ...} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
68 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [0123]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 80 10 00 40 ...} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
97 Decode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 12 34 ...} will be decoded as ‘1234’
98 Decode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 ... 12 34 ...} will be decoded as ‘3412’
Other Not used

Table below shows position of a sample value ‘341’ (0x0155) in a Modbus message and the RegOffset required to read this value.

Table 10.28 Modbus Master Register Offset sample values
RegOffset Modbus Message
0 {01 04 ... 01 55 00 00 ...}
1 {01 04 ... 00 00 01 55 ...}

DOTable group and DO node

Group node DOTable and child element nodes DO are used to create DO information objects for sending control commands to outstation. Each created DO can be used as a destination for any DO information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Command execution procedure is as follows: Slave protocol instance receives a control command from the upstream Master station and forwards to the destination DO object. Current communication protocol instance validates and sends a command to the outstation based on the DO settings configured below. Please refer to the section DOTable group and DO node for more information on how to use DO as a destination.

Tip

DOTable group and DO nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. DO information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO child element nodes below. There are 5 DO information objects configured using 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0"/>
     <DO Index="1" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="1"/>
     <DO Index="2" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="2" Qualifier="0x01"/>
     <DO Index="3" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="4" Total="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Qualifier="0x00" PulseDuration="500" Total="1" Name="Output 1" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

 1...65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.CtrlMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.

Table 10.30 Modbus Master DO internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DO internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DO object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0)
xxxx.xxx1 DO object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1)
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DO is enabled, command will be sent to outstation
1xxx.xxxx DO is disabled, command will not be sent to outstation
Bits 1..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

11. IEC61850 Client

This section describes how to configure IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. IEC61850 standard specifies a System Configuration Language (SCL) for files which are used to store configuration data of the IED. Most commonly used files are IED Capability Description (ICD), Configured IED Description (CID) and System Configuration Description (SCD). CID or SCD file is required for each IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. It contains communication capabilities and settings of a Server station (IED) we would like to communicate to. In addition to CID/SCD file a XML configuration file is required. It contains IO object table and additional protocol-related settings. The same pairs of CID/SCD and XML files can be used for multiple IEC61850 Client communication protocol instances. It becomes very useful if multiple outstations have identical sets of IO objects.

Name and location path of the configuration files is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. Files ‘IED_IO.xml‘ and ‘IED.cid‘ are used as a sample. Enter names of the files in IEC61850cl.XMLpath and IEC61850cl.CIDpath attributes of a communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IED_IO.xml” and CIDpath=”IED.cid” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the files are stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC61850 Client configuration file (e.g. ‘IED_IO.xml‘) must have a root object node IEC61850clConfig which has 2 mandatory child group object nodes VersionControl; ProtocolCfg and 4 optional child group object nodes DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable please see the sample below.

<IEC61850clConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC61850cl" … version="1.00">
   <VersionControl conf="4.00" date="2016-01-25" time="12:00:09"/>
   <ProtocolCfg>
      <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10"/>
      <TransportSettings CallingTSEL="0x0A" SourceREF="0x04"/>
      …
   </ProtocolCfg>
   <DITable>
      <DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST"/>
      …
   </DITable>
   <AITable>
      <AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX"/>
      …
   </AITable>
   <DOTable>
      <DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO"/>
      …
   </DOTable>
   <AOTable>
      <AO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Mod" fc="CO"/>
      …
   </AOTable>
</IEC61850clConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable group nodes form the IO object table of the IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables 11.20; 11.22; 11.25 and 11.27 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group node

ProtocolCfg group and its child element nodes contain protocol-related settings of the IEC61850 Client instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg node and all available child element nodes below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element node.

<ProtocolCfg>
       <CommsSettings … />
       <TransportSettings … />
       <SessionSettings … />
       <PresentationSettings … />
       <AssociationSettings … />
       <ScsmSettings … />
       <AppSettings … />
       <ServiceSettings … />
       <Timeouts … />
       <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" />
Table 11.1 IEC61850 Client CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

OfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 6 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated after TCP socket has been closed. Default 6 seconds - station status will change to OFFLINE 6 seconds after TCP socket has been closed by either host.

PostOfflineDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)
