<TransportSettings CallingTSEL="0001" SourceREF="15" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 11.2 IEC61850 Client TransportSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

CallingTSEL

 Up to 8 hexadecimal characters 0...F 0001 Identifier of the calling Transport-Selector used for outgoing Connection Request [CR-TPDU] message.
SourceREF 1...65535 10 Reference selected by the transport entity initiating the Connection Request [CR-TPDU] message to identify the requested transport connection.

Flags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Miscellaneous settings of the Transport layer. See table 11.3 for description.
Table 11.3 Transport layer flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Transport layer flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Ignore destination reference [DST-REF] of the received [CC-TPDU] message (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 Check destination reference [DST-REF] of the received [CC-TPDU] message. Communication will not be established if reference is incorrect.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Ignore [Calling Transport Selector] and [Called Transport Selector] identifiers of the received [CC-TPDU] message (default value)
xxxx.xx1x Check [Calling Transport Selector] and [Called Transport Selector] identifiers of the received [CC-TPDU] message. Communication will not be established if the received [Calling Transport Selector] doesn’t match “OSI-TSEL” in the SCL file or [Called Transport Selector] is different from [CR-TPDU] message value.

Basic Types are not read by default, but only if either of following conditions is met:
/ AppSettings.Flags Bit[0] is set which forces to always read LD directory with [GetLogicalDeviceDirectory];
/ IED supports Dynamic Datasets and Dynamic Report Blocks (with empty DatSet=””) are not specified in the SCL file.
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.x1xx Read Basic Types of all objects when station goes online with [GetDataDirectory] Basic Types are not read by default, only in circumstatnces described above.

AppSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of AppSettings element node.

Please see sample AppSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AppSettings IgnoreTimetags="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1" bufTime="0" orCat="3" orIdent="LEANDC" Flags="0x0000"/>
Table 11.14 IEC61850 Client AppSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no threshold, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.

AIDeadband

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature

AIPercent

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc startup
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after system leandc
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
bufTime 0...232 - 2 0 msec Interval in milliseconds for the buffering of internal notifications before Information Report is generated [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables buffering and Information Reports are generated instantly.
orCat 1...8 3 Originator category value for outgoing commands [IEC61850-7-3:2011]. Default value 3 = [remote-control]
orIdent 64 chars LEANDC Originator identification value for outgoing commands [IEC61850-7-3:2011].

Flags

 0...65535 or 0x0000...0xFFFF 0x0000 Miscellaneous settings of the Application layer. See table 11.15 for description.
Table 11.15 Application layer flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx.xxxx.xxxx] 0x0000...0xFFFF Application layer flags is 16 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...65535 and hex 0x0000...0xFFFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xxx0 Don’t read the LD directory [GetLogicalDeviceDirectory] when station goes online if IED supports only static datasets (default value)
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xxx1 Read the LD directory [GetLogicalDeviceDirectory] when station goes online even if IED supports only static datasets. IED initialization will take longer if this bit is enabled, however it offers extra checks. Object directory received from IED will be matched against SCL file and any inconsistencies will be reported.
Bit 1 xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xx0x Process reports generated after Enhanced security command completion (default value)
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xx1x Ignore reports generated after Enhanced security command completion. This bit has to be used only for IEDs that doesn’t generate a report when Enhanced security Direct or SBO command is complete. If not set command will be removed only after Application timeout expiration.
Bit 2 xxxx.xxxx xxxx.x0xx Ignore millisecond accuracy of timetags received from IED (default value)
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.x1xx Use millisecond accuracy of timetags received from IED. Some IEDs report lower accuracy if the IED is not synchronized. Enabling this setting will result in rounding of milliseconds based on the accuracy and the timetag may appear different from the value IED has recorded in the internal event list.
Bit 4 xxxx.xxxx xxx0.xvxx Use [Resv] attribute value of the Unbufferred report control block received from IED (default value) IEC61850 client tries to reserve only unbuffered report control blocks that are not already reserved by another client.
xxxx.xxxx xxx1.xxxx Ignore [Resv] attribute value of the Unbufferred report control block received from IED. IEC61850 client tries to reserve unbuffered report control blocks even if already reserved by another client.
Bit 8 xxxx.xxx0 xxxx.xxxx Enable only Report Blocks with linked static datasets that contain defined DI/AI objects (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 xxxx.xxxx Enable all Report Blocks that exist in the SCL file. This setting applies only to Report Blocks that are defined in the SCL file.
Bits 3;5...7;9...15 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 11.16 IEC61850 Client ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See table 11.17 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 11.17 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires
Bits 4...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" Response="5"/>
Table 11.18 IEC61850 Client Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1...232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1...232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.
Select 1...232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, object is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.
Response 1...232 - 1 5 sec Response timeout in seconds. Connection to IED will be closed if no response to a sent message has been received within this timeout.

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic GI="600" intgPd="60000" />
Table 11.19 IEC61850 Client Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
GI 0...232 - 1 0 sec Periodic General Interrogation command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic General Interrogation command.
intgPd 0...232 - 2 0 msec Common interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. This attribute is used for all DI/AI objects which doesn’t have DI.intgPd or AI.intgPd attribute specified in their element node. Value 0 disables integrity reports.

DITable group and DI node

Group node DITable and child element nodes DI are used to create DI information objects to receive status information from an IED. Each created DI can be used as a source for any DI information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Data received from an IED will be forwarded to the DI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section DITable group and DI node for more information on how to use DI information object as a source.

Please see sample DITable group and DI child element nodes below.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST"/>
     <DI Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Loc" fc="ST"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST" Qualifier="0" InterDelay="10000" IndetDelay="0" daName="stVal" DSnum="1" TrgOps="0x00" intgPd="0" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 11.20 IEC61850 Client DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
ldInst 1...64 chars n/a Logical Device instance from SCL file e.g. ‘LD0’
prefix 0...11 chars n/a Prefix of the Logical Node name from SCL file e.g.’DA’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have prefix. Leave blank i.e. prefix=”” in this case.
lnClass 4 chars n/a Logical Node Class from SCL file e.g. ‘XCBR’
lnInst 0...1010 - 1 n/a Logical Node Instance from SCL file e.g. ‘1’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have instance. Leave blank i.e. lnInst=”” in this case.
doName 1...64 chars n/a Data object name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘Pos’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘A.phsA’
fc 2 chars n/a Functional Constraint from SCL file e.g. ‘ST’

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 11.21 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

InterDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate state of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate state) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

IndetDelay

 0...232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) state) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
daName 1...64 chars stVal Data attribute name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘stVal’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘cVal.mag.f’ Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

DSnum

 1...100 automatic Number of the dynamic dataset that will include this object. Value 100 is reserved as an indicator to reuse a static dataset predefined in SCL if it contains this object. It is recommended not to use this attribute, unless you fully understand implications. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will be grouped in datasets automatically if omitted.

TrgOps

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Information Report trigger options. See table 11.24 for Trigger Options description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

intgPd

 0...232 - 2 0 Interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables integrity reports. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.Qualifier

Table 11.21 IEC61850 Client DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0 for [SPS] and [SPC] classes and ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [DPS] and [DPC] classes)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1 for [SPS] and [SPC] classes and ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [DPS] and [DPC] classes)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from IED
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from IED
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Include this DI in persistent dynamic dataset. IED retains persistent dynamically created datasets if communication to IEC61850 client is lost until IED is restarted/powered off.
x1xx.xxxx Include this DI in non-persistent dynamic dataset. IED automatically deletes non-persistent dynamically created datasets when communication to IEC61850 client is lost. This option only applies if IED supports dynamic dataset creation.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 1;2;4 Any Bits reserved for future use

AITable group and AI node

Group node AITable and child element nodes AI are used to create AI information objects to receive analog information from an IED. Each created AI can be used as a source for any AI information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Analog data received from an IED will be forwarded to the AI information object of the Slave protocol instance and then to the upstream Master station. Please refer to the section AITable group and AI node for more information on how to use AI information object as a source.

Please see sample AITable group and AI child element nodes below.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsB" fc="MX"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" daName="cVal.mag.f" DSnum="1" TrgOps="0x00" intgPd="0" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 11.22 IEC61850 Client AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Index

 0...232 - 8 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
ldInst 1...64 chars n/a Logical Device instance from SCL file e.g. ‘LD0’
prefix 0...11 chars n/a Prefix of the Logical Node name from SCL file e.g.’CPH’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have prefix. Leave blank i.e. prefix=”” in this case.
lnClass 4 chars n/a Logical Node Class from SCL file e.g. ‘MMXU’
lnInst 0...1010 - 1 n/a Logical Node Instance from SCL file e.g. ‘1’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have instance. Leave blank i.e. lnInst=”” in this case.
doName 1...64 chars n/a Data object name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘Pos’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘A.phsA’
fc 2 chars n/a Functional Constraint from SCL file e.g. ‘MX’

Qualifier

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See table 11.23 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Coeff

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Deadband

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from the analog value stored in the database in order to create absolute deadband range (range is: ‘oldvalue - deadband’ … ‘oldvalue + deadband’). New incoming analog value is checked against limits of this deadband and an event is generated if value is outside. Value 0 disables deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

Percent

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and an event will be generated if last received analog value exceeds the value stored in the leandc database plus/minus defined Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate absolute deadband based on the last analog value stored in the database. When absolute deadband range is calculated, the same procedure as described above applies. Value 0 disables percent deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration if not used.

StartOffset

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ZeroDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

Offset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

OffsetDeadband

*

 0 or +1.18×10-38 ... +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

NonZeroOffset

*

 0 or ±1.18×10-38 ... ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
daName 1...64 chars cVal.mag.f Data attribute name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘stVal’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘cVal.mag.f’ Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

DSnum

 1...100 automatic Number of the dynamic dataset that will include this object. Value 100 is reserved as an indicator to reuse a static dataset predefined in SCL if it contains this object. It is recommended not to use this attribute, unless you fully understand implications. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will be grouped in datasets automatically if omitted.

TrgOps

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Information Report trigger options. See table 11.24 for Trigger Options description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

intgPd

 0...232 - 2 0 Interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables integrity reports. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from IED

DOTable group and DO node

Group node DOTable and child element nodes DO are used to create DO information objects for sending control commands to IED. Each created DO can be used as a destination for any DO information object defined in the IO table of any Slave protocol instance. Command execution procedure is as follows: Slave protocol instance receives a control command from the upstream Master station and forwards to the destination DO object. Current communication protocol instance validates and sends a command to IED based on the DO settings configured below. Please refer to the section DOTable group and DO node for more information on how to use DO as a destination.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO child element nodes below.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO"/>
     <DO Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="BlkOpn" fc="CO"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO" Qualifier="0x00" Name="CB command" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element node can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

12. Logfiles

Leandc features a raw communication traffic and decoded application level information recording to logfiles for supervision and maintenance purposes. Fixed name XML configuration file lelogger.xml contains settings to enable logfiles. This file must be kept in the same directory as leandc.xml file. Its path and name can’t be changed.

lelogger.xml configuration file consists of a root object node SystemConfig which has 3 optional child group object nodes VersionControl; CommsCfg; EventCfg, please see the sample below.

<SystemConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/lelogger" … version="1.00">
      <VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
      <CommsCfg>
         <LOGGER Index="6" LogFlags="0x7F" Logfile="Log/ma2"/>
         …
         <HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
         …
         <PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
      </CommsCfg>
      <EventCfg>
         <EVENTLOG Index="104" LogFlags="0x3F" HourLimit="0" Logfile="Events/SL104_1"/>
         …
      </EventCfg>
</SystemConfig>

Tip

lelogger.xml configuration file is optional and leandc is able to run normally without it.
Node names are case sensitive.

LOGGER and HWLOG nodes

LOGGER and HWLOG nodes contain settings for raw communication traffic logging and these nodes are children of CommsCfg group node. Following functionality is available:

  • Record all raw traffic over a serial/Ethernet interface - HWLOG node;
  • Filter and record traffic related to a specific communication protocol instance - LOGGER node;

Configuration may contain both nodes at the same time in any combination. However only 1 logfile per protocol instance and 1 logfile per hardware interface is allowed.

Please see sample CommsCfg group node and LOGGER and HWLOG child element nodes below. The sample below shows 2 logfiles for recording filtered traffic related to particular communication protocol instance and 1 logfile for recording all traffic over a serial interface.

<CommsCfg>
   <LOGGER Index="5" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/serial101" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="4"/>
   <LOGGER Index="6" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Log/tcpserv104"/>
   <HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
</CommsCfg>

Please see all available attributes of the LOGGER and HWLOG nodes below:

<LOGGER Index="5" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Log/serial101" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="Europe/Riga" Name="IED logfile" />
<HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC" Name="COM port logfile" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

LOGGER and HWLOG attributes

Table 12.1 LOGGER and HWLOG attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1...254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a specific communication protocol instance. Use value of the Index attribute of any communication protocol instance to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for LOGGER node and must not be used for HWLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1...254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index ; TCPSERVER.Index ; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for HWLOG node and must not be used for LOGGER node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.

LogFlags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Select type of the messages to be logged. See table 12.2 for description. Logfile will not be created if the value is 0.

Logfile

 Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.log’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.log’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (sample value ‘Log/abc’, where ‘Log’ is the name of the folder and ‘abc’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Logfile initialization settings. See table 12.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default settings will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0...12 4 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 4 hours – total of 6 files will be created daily at 00:00, 04:00, 08:00, 12:00, 16:00, 20:00) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default settings will be used if omitted.
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of the recorded information based on the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* List of files created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings can be found in section Logfile samples.

Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported Logfile will not be created, if the value is 0.
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Link layer (of the IEC60870-5-101 communication protocol) or Transport layer (of the IEC60870-5-104 communication protocol) message recording disabled
xxxx.xxx1 Link layer (of the IEC60870-5-101 communication protocol) or Transport layer (of the IEC60870-5-104 communication protocol) message recording enabled
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Incoming message logging disabled
xxxx.xx1x Incoming message logging enabled
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Outgoing message logging disabled
xxxx.x1xx Outgoing message logging enabled

xxx1.xxxx Socket connection status and [Started]; [Stopped] state information of the IEC60870-5-104 protocol instance or link layer state information of the IEC60870-5-101 protocol instance logging enabled
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Only applicable to IEC60870-5-101 protocol instances, don’t log the transmitted message echo (if it exists)
1xxx.xxxx Only applicable to IEC60870-5-101 protocol instances, log the transmitted message echo (if it exists)

PCAPLOG

PCAPLOG node enables to capture traffic through a specific or any Ethernet interfaces in a pcap format. PCAPLOG node is a child of CommsCfg group node.

Please see sample CommsCfg group and PCAPLOG child element node below.

<CommsCfg>
   <PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
</CommsCfg>

Important

Group node CommsCfg may contain only one PCAPLOG node. PCAPLOG must be the last in the group after all LOGGER and HWLOG nodes, if there are any.

Please see all available attributes of the PCAPLOG node below:

<PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" Name="pcap trace" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

Only one PCAPLOG node can be defined. Use LogFlags attribute to enable capture on all Ethernet interfaces, if required.

LogFlags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Capture filter specifications. See table 12.4 for description. Capture is disabled if value is 0.

PCAPLOG.LogFlags

Table 12.4 Capture filter flags
Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Filter flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported Capture is disabled if the value is 0.
Bits 0,1 xxxx.xx00 Reserved - don’t use.
xxxx.xx01 Capture traffic through all available Ethernet interfaces. Traffic will not be filtered by IP address.
xxxx.xx10 Capture traffic trough a single Ethernet interface, the one used for communication.
xxxx.xx11 Filter captured traffic by IP address. Only messages with matching Source or Destination IP address will be captured. Address from TCPSERVER.ServerIPaddr ; TCPCLIENT.ServerIPaddr or UDP.RemoteIPaddr attribute is used as a filter.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Capture filter by port number is disabled
xxxx.x1xx Capture filter by port number is enabled. Only messages with matching Source or Destination Port number will be captured. Port number from TCPSERVER.Port ; TCPCLIENT.Port or UDP.RemotePort attribute is used as a filter.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx SSH (TCP port 22) traffic capture disabled
x1xx.xxxx SSH (TCP port 22) traffic capture enabled
Bits 3...5;7 Any Bits reserved for future use

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes contain settings for decoded application level information (DI/AI/DO/AO object types, addresses, values, etc) logging and these nodes are children of EventCfg group node. Following functionality is available:

  • Record all decoded information over a serial/Ethernet interface - HWEVENTLOG node;
  • Filter and record decoded information related to a specific communication protocol instance - EVENTLOG node;

Configuration may contain both nodes at the same time in any combination. However only 1 logfile per protocol instance and 1 logfile per hardware interface is allowed.

Please see sample EventCfg group node and EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG child element nodes below. The sample below shows 2 logfiles for recording decoded information of a particular communication protocol instance and 1 logfile for recording decoded information over a serial interface.

<EventCfg>
   <EVENTLOG Index="5" LogFlags="0x3F" Logfile="Events/serial101" HourLimit="0" Mode="0"/>
   <EVENTLOG Index="6" LogFlags="0x0C" Logfile="Events/tcpserv104"/>
   <HWEVENTLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x40" Logfile="Events/COM1_events" HourLimit="0"/>
</EventCfg>

Please see all available attributes of the EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes below:

<EVENTLOG Index="5" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Events/101slave" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="Europe/Riga" Name="IED Events" />
<HWEVENTLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Events/COM1" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC" Name="All IED Events" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG attributes

Table 12.5 EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1...254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a specific communication protocol instance. Use value of the Index attribute of any communication protocol instance to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for EVENTLOG node and must not be used for HWEVENTLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1...254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index ; TCPSERVER.Index ; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for HWEVENTLOG node and must not be used for EVENTLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.

LogFlags

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x00 Select type of the decoded information to be logged. See table 12.6 for description. Logfile will not be created if value is 0.

Logfile

 Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.event’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.event’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (sample value ‘Events/abc’, where ‘Events’ is the name of the folder and ‘abc’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0...255 or 0x00...0xFF 0x01 Logfile initialization settings. See table 12.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default settings will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0...12 6 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 6 hours – total of 4 files will be created daily at 00:00, 06:00, 12:00, 18:00) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default settings will be used if omitted.
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of the recorded information based on the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.
Name Max 100 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* List of files created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings can be found in section Logfile samples.

EVENTLOG.LogFlags

Table 12.6 Event logfile flags
Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported Logfile will not be created, if the value is 0.
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Received/sent spontaneous (event) DI information will not be logged
xxxx.xxx1 Received/sent spontaneous (event) DI information will be logged
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Received/sent spontaneous (event) AI information will not be logged
xxxx.xx1x Received/sent spontaneous (event) AI information will be logged
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Received/sent control/setpoint command information will not be logged
xxxx.x1xx Received/sent control/setpoint command information will be logged
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Processed command information and error messages will not be logged
xxxx.1xxx Processed command information and error messages will be logged
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Received/sent static (General Interrogation) DI information will not be logged
xxx1.xxxx Received/sent static (General Interrogation) DI information will be logged
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Received/sent static (General Interrogation) AI information will not be logged
xx1x.xxxx Received/sent static (General Interrogation) AI information will be logged
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Received/sent cyclic AI information will not be recorded to event logfile
x1xx.xxxx Received/sent cyclic AI information will be logged
Bit 7 Any Bits reserved for future use

LOGGER.Mode and EVENTLOG.Mode

Table 12.7 Logfile initialization Mode
Bits Value Description
Mode [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00...0xFF Logfile initialization Mode is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0...255 and hex 0x00...0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 New logfile will be created every time leandc is being started/restarted. This means total number of files created each day will reflect how many times leandc was started/restarted.
xxxx.xxx1 New file will not be created if there is a logfile which was created the same date upon leandc start/restart. New messages will be appended at the end of the existing file. This means there will be only one file created each day, regardless of how many times leandc was started/restarted.
Bits 1...7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Logfile samples

This section provides information on how communication and event logfiles are created based on default settings as well as contents of each file.

New communication logfile is created every 4 hours based on the default value of the LOGGER.HourLimit attribute. In addition to that new file will be created every time leandc is started/restarted based on the default value “0x00” of the LOGGER.Mode attribute. Example below shows 2 lists of files created if leandc runs continuously and if being restarted.

Tip

File creation date and hour (yyyy-mm-dd_hh) is automatically added to the name of the file specified in LOGGER.Logfile attribute. This is a sample list of files created, if leandc is running continuously without being restarted.

  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_00.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_04.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_08.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_12.log’

Time-tag (hhmmss) is added to the name of the file which is created after leandc restart. Time-tag will be added to the name of the new file only if there is an existing file which was created at the same hour range (4 hours). This is a sample list of files created, if leandc was restarted at 14:04:13 and 14:07:32 and then switched off at 17:00:00 and started at 21:10:10.

  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_12.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_140413.log’ <- new file created after leandc restart at 14:04:13, time-tag is added because file created within a 4 hour range (at 12:00:00) exists
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_140732.log’ <- new file created after leandc restart at 14:04:13, time-tag is added because file created within a 4 hour range (at 12:00:00) exists
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_16.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_20.log’ <- new file created when leandc started at 21:10:10, no time-tag because there are no files created within a 4 hour range (from 20:00:00 to 23:59:59)

Default settings of the event files are slightly different. New event logfile is created every 6 hours based on the default value of the EVENTLOG.HourLimit attribute. However new file will not be created upon leandc restart based on the default value “0x01” of the EVENTLOG.Mode attribute. If an existing file created within the same hour range (6 hours) is found after leandc restart, new entires will appended to that file. Example below shows the list of files created if leandc runs continuously and if being restarted.

Tip

File creation date and hour (yyyy-mm-dd_hh) is automatically added to the name of the file specified in EVENTLOG.Logfile attribute. This is a sample list of files created, if leandc was restarted at 14:04:13.

  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_00.event’
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_06.event’
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_12.event’ <- leandc restart at 14:04:13, no new file is created because file within a 6 hour range exists. New entries are appended to this file.
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_18.event’

Contents of a typical communication logfile is shown below:

17:14:34.170 INFO    ONLINE
17:14:34.205 COMM -> 10 40 01 41 16
17:14:34.205 COMM <- 10 00 01 01 16
17:14:34.413 COMM -> 68 0F 0F 68 73 01 67 01 06 01 00 00 42 86 0E 11 CB 05 0D A7 16
17:14:34.414 COMM <- 10 20 01 21 16
17:14:34.625 COMM -> 68 09 09 68 53 01 64 01 06 01 00 00 14 D4 16

Raw traffic that is captured over a communication interface is recorded to a file along with some is additional information. Each entry (row) in the file represents successfully decoded protocol message and is prefixed with a time-tag, log entry type and direction identifier. Timetag represents the internal time when the message was received/sent. Log entry type may contain values listed in the table below:

Table 12.8 Logfile entry types
Entry Type Description
COMM Successfully decoded protocol message
INFO Additional status information e.g. ONLINE, OFFLINE, etc
ERR Failed protocol messages and timeouts
Direction identifier shows incoming/outgoing direction of a message as follows:
<- Outgoing message (sent by leandc)
-> Incoming message (received by leandc)
Directions are the same for Slave/Master communication protocol instances.

Contents of a typical event logfile is shown below:

    Time             Info    Type    ASDUadr InfAddr Value   QualHex TimeTag                 Description
12:00:09.470 SU      SPNTAI  36      400     2101    63.88   0x00    2015-07-31 09:00:09.470
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTAI  36      400     39      8.45    0x00    2015-07-31 09:00:12.942
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTAI  34      400     57      24      0x00    2015-07-31 09:00:12.942
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTDI  31      400     1002    OFF     0x01    2015-07-31 09:00:14.873
12:02:59.720         >CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05                            Direct execute command received, validated and forwarded to Master protocol
12:02:59.846         <CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05                            Execute Confirmation sent successfully
12:02:01.347         <CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05                            Termination sent successfully

Decoded information is arranged in a tab separated columns. The layout of the file is aimed to present a decoded information readable without additional tools, yet tab separated columns make importing event file into a spreadsheet an easy task. List of columns of the event logfile is shown in the table below:

Table 12.9 Event logfile columns
Column Description
Time Internal time when the event was received. Summer Time [SU] flag may be added to the time stamp.
Info Type of the event. See table 12.10 for description.
Type ASDU typeID of the message.
ASDUadr Common Address of ASDU [CAA].
InfAddr Information object address [IOA].
Value Value of the event. Decoded Floating point and Integer analog values can be easily distinguished by presence of a decimal point. Decimal point is only used for Floating point values, Integers doesn’t have it. Status information has 4 or 2 states (i.e. ON, OFF, INTER, INDET) which are shown depending on single or double message type. In case of control command decimal value of command qualifier including additional information (e.g. [Short pulse]) is shown in this column.
QualHex Hexadecimal value of the object qualifier.
TimeTag Time-tag of the event as received/sent to peer station. This column is populated only if event message has a time-tag. Summer Time [SU] flag may be added to the time tag.
Description Additional information on the command execution progress.
Table 12.10 Event logfile Info types
Info Description
>CMD Received control or setpoint command in the context of Slave protocol instance. Received confirmation or termination in the context of Master protocol instance.
<CMD Sent control or setpoint command in the context of Master protocol instance. Sent confirmation or termination in the context of Slave protocol instance.
>CMDN Received negative confirmation or termination, only applies to Master protocol instances.
<CMDN Sent negative confirmation or termination, only applies to Slave protocol instances.
>CMDERR Received control or setpoint command validation failed, command is immediately rejected, only applies to Slave protocol instances.
CMD Additional information on command execution progress.
CMDERR Internal error occurred while command being processed. Please contact vendor if this type of error appears.
SPNTDI Spontaneous status information (DI Event).
DI Static status information (e.g. as a response to General Interrogation).
SPNTAI Spontaneous analog information (AI Event).
AI Static analog information (e.g. as a response to General Interrogation).
AICYC Cyclic/periodic analog information.
AIBSCN Background scan analog information.
ERR Internal error. Please contact vendor if this type of error appears.

13. Configuration version control

All XML configuration files must contain version control element node where user can enter a unique number to control configuration file version along with file creation date and time. Each configuration file has its own version number and it is not related to any other XML files. If particular XML file is being modified by web configuration tool, the version number is automatically incremented by 1 and modification date and time is recorded.

Version control node must have 3 attributes conf; date; time please see the sample below.

<VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>

VersionControl attributes

Table 13.1 VersionControl attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
conf 0.01...65535 User assigned version number of the particular XML file. Number will be automatically incremented by 1 when particular XML file is being modified by web configuration tool.
date date notation YYYY-MM-DD Date when particular configuration file was created or modified.
time time notation HH:MM:SS Time when particular configuration file was created or modified.

Important

All attributes are mandatory.

14. Annexes

Analog value processing

This annex contains information about analog value processing, scaling options and application examples. All analog values are converted to Short Floating-point (32bit) numbers internally before scaling takes place. All AI scaling attributes used in this document: Coeff, Deadband, Percent, StartOffset, ZeroDeadband, Offset, OffsetDeadband, NonZeroOffset are Short Floating-point numbers. The value range is given for each of these attributes and values have to be specified either in decimal or scientific notation. Sample values are shown in the table below.

Table 14.1 Analog value notations
Decimal Scientific
1520.3 1.5203e3
-11 -1.1e1
0.00152 1.52e-3
-0.0456 -4.56e-2

Important

Precision of the Short Floating-point number is 7 decimal digits regardless of position of the decimal point. This applies to decimal and scientific notations. For example there are 7 decimal digits in numbers ‘1234567’ ‘1234.567’ ‘1.234567e3’ which is the maximum accuracy. Numbers with more decimal digits will be rounded.

Analog value scaling

Analog value scaling attributes Coeff, StartOffset, ZeroDeadband, Offset, OffsetDeadband, NonZeroOffset exist in Master and Slave protocol instances and scaling processes are independent of each other. This means analog value received from an outstation will be scaled at Master protocol instance first and then by a Slave protocol instance before sending the value out. It is recommended to enable scaling at Master protocol instances that receive analog values from outstations, but there are no restrictions that would prevent using scaling at Slave protocol instances. Analog value scaling sequence in shown in the flowchart below.

AI scaling sequence

Tip

StartOffset attribute automatically sets Invalid [IV] quality flag when forcing analog value to zero ‘0’. This is designed to detect failure of a 4-20mA tranducer (or similar) connected to an Analog Input. 4mA current is expecet when transducer is connected even if it is not measuring anything. If the current drops below 4mA Invalid [IV] quality flag is used to indicate a transducer failure or disconnect. ZeroDeadband attribute works alongside StartOffset in order to suppress noise around 4mA value and its use is receommended.

Scaling calculator below shows how leandc analog scaling actually works. Enter a numeric value in the box ‘Start value’ and the ‘Result’ box will show the value after scaling has been applied. Scaling attributes are arranged in the order they are applied as shown in the sequence flowchart above. Calculator shows intermediate values after each attribute as well as basic math that was applied in each step. Any changes to scaling attributes are applied instantly and the result will be updated accordingly. The ‘Copy’ button on the top left corner can be used to copy scaling attributes and their entered values to clipboard. They will be formated in XML syntax and can be pasted directly into XML file.

StartOffset ZeroDeadband Offset OffsetDeadband NonZeroOffset Coeff
Start value Result
 

AI scaling calculator

Range calculator shown below enables to calculate Offset and Coeff attribute values based on ranges of analog values before and after scaling. The range of values before scaling takes place (e.g. range of values expected to be received from outstation) have to be entered into ‘Input Range’ boxes and the range of resulting values (e.g. expected from leandc) have to be entered into ‘Output Range’ boxes. ‘Calculate’ button will update Offset and Coeff attributes of the scaling calculator above. Updated attributes will be highlighted yellow.

Application example shown below can be used to calculate StartOffset, Offset, NonZeroOffset and Coeff attributes by selecting various devices as a source of an analog value. LEANDC box performs scaling based on attributes of the scaling calculator above. ‘Analog Input Module’ checkbox simulates the Analog Input Module connected to LEANDC. Its input range in milliamps and output integer range (based on ADC bit count) can be selected. Changing analog value at Analog Module Input will update value at Module output and LEANDC output (after scaling). The ‘Calculate’ button must be pressed when devices are enabled/disabled or input/output ranges changed in order to update StartOffset, Offset, NonZeroOffset and Coeff attributes of the scaling calculator above. Updated attributes will be highlighted yellow. Measuring transducer and Voltage/Current transformer can be enabled/disabled with drop-down box and checkbox respectively. Please note the transducer can be enabled only if Analog Input Module is already enabled and Voltage/Current transformer can be enabled if both transducer and Analog Input Module are enabled. The input/output ranges can be selected from pre-defined values listed in drop-down boxes of each device and custom values can be entered manually.

AI application example

Received AI processing

Flowchart below shows AI value processing when IEC60870-5-101/103/104 Master protocol instance receives AI object from outstation. This processing takes place after AI scaling has been completed, refer to previous annexes for additional information on AI scaling.

Received AI processing flowchart

The figure below shows how a real time value received from outstation will be processed if AI.Deadband attribute is enabled. Internal database will be updated and AI event will get generated every time a real time value exceeds ‘static deadband’. Thresholds of the ‘static deadband’ are calculated based on previous value stored in the database. Attribute AI.Deadband = 2 is used as an example.

AI.Deadband processing sample

The figure below shows how a real time value received from outstation will be processed if AI.Percent attribute is enabled. Internal database will be updated and AI event will get generated every time a real time value exceeds ‘dynamic deadband’. Thresholds of the ‘dynamic deadband’ are calculated based on previous value stored in the database. Attribute AI.Percent = 20 is used as an example.

AI.Percent processing sample

Time Zone specification

It is possible to adjust incoming and outgoing message timestamps in case if LEANDC unit communicates to the peer station that uses a different time zone. Conventionally timezone and DST information is kept in the so-called ‘Time Zone Database’ that consists of a set of TZ format files, these are published and maintained by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA), please refer to their website (http://www.iana.org/time-zones) for more information. In general there is a TZ file for each country in the world where information related to DST and other time adjustments is recorded. These files can be found in LEANDC operating system directory:

/usr/share/zoneinfo

leandc firmware will attempt to locate a TZ file matching the name specified in a TimeZone attribute in this system folder. If a matching file is not found, leandc firmware will use System default time zone which means the timestamps for the particular communication protocol instance will not be adjusted. Please find the list of most commonly used time zones below:

<TimeZone>UTC</TimeZone>
<TimeZone>Europe/Riga</TimeZone>
<TimeZone>Europe/London</TimeZone>

If required the System default time zone can be changed as described in Leandc SSH manual section ‘Change Leandc operating system time zone‘. The System default time zone is used for maintaining internal time of the LEANDC unit. Internal time is used for time synchronization, time-stamping logfile records, creating logfile names, etc.

> TimeSync attribute added to IEC60870-5-104 Master Broadcast node to enable broadcast Common Address of ASDU (CAA) for outgoing Time Synchronization commands;
> TimeSync attribute added to IEC60870-5-104 Slave ASDUSettings node to enable internal clock synchronization when command is received;
> LEIODC-X32-3100, LEIODC-X10-3100 and THT2 types added to Modbus Master Hardcoded node
V24 29/06/2015 AK
> DIEventStartup and AIEventStartup attributes added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave ASDUSettings node;
> OffIndex attribute added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave DI node for single to double point indication conversion;
> DIInterDelay and DIIndetDelay attributes added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave ASDUSettings node and corresponding attributes InterDelay and IndetDelay added to DI node;
> Bit[5] added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave DI qualifier attribute which enables to select time tag when single status information is converted to double;
> ChatterFilter attribute added to Modbus Master DI node;
> PulseDuration attribute added to Modbus Master DO node;
> LEIODC-C32-3100 type added to Modbus Master Hardcoded node;
V23 24/03/2015 AK
> IgnoreWhileLinkcnt attribute added to IEC60870-5-101 Master LinkSettings node;
V22 15/02/2015 AK
> Interface and Test attributes added to UART node;
> TimeZone attribute added to all logfile configuration nodes;
> DOType and AOType attributes added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocols. These can be used to create common filters for incoming command ASDU types;
> ForwardGI attribute added to all ASDUSettings nodes. GI commands will be forwarded to downstream outstations if received from upstream station by default. This feature can be disabled with ForwardGI attribute;
> ServiceSettings node and attributes added to all protocol configurations;
> DIEvent and AIEvent attributes renamed to DIEVsize and AIEVsize respectively;
> DIEVmult and AIEVmult attributes added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocol BufferSizes nodes;
> DisabledNT attribute removed, service settings can be used from now on to enable the functionality;
> PostOfflineDelay attribute added to all Master protocol configurations. Together with ServiceSettings node and attributes this extends configuration flexibility of DI/AI object quality marking when stations goes OFFLINE;
> Reset attribute added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Master protocol Broadcast node. This enables to send Reset Process commands to dowstream stations using Broadcast Common address of ASDU;
> Miscellaneous node added to IEC60870-5-101 Master protocol. Attributes TimeSyncIOA and DayOfWeek enable to customize Information Object Address (IOA) and supress Day Of Week use in outgoing Time Synchronziation commands respectively;
V21 28/11/2014 AK
Modbusma communication protocol instance added;
Leandc XML configuration manual is HTML-based from now on;
V20 09/10/2014 AK DIEventStartup attribute added to IEC60870-5-101/3/4 Master protocol configuration;
V19 26/06/2014 AK
All protocol setting node elements migrated to attributes;
New option to mark DI/AI objects with NT bit when outstation goes offline or is disabled using service command. IEC60870-5-101/4 Master protocol attributes OfflineNTDelay and DisabledNT;
Option to send valid AIEVs to SCADA system on leandc startup in order to initialize the state of legacy spontaneous-only AIEVs. Valid AIEVs with 0 value will be sent after a number of seconds specified in LegacyAIEVinitdelay attribute on system startup in order to initialize SCADA database and make it ready to receive first legacy AIEV.
StationID attribute added to IEC104Csl node;
TypeID attribute added to IEC60870-5-101/4 Master DI/AI objects;
SingleCharACK attribute added for IEC60870-5-101 Slave protocol allowing to respond with single character (0xE5 or 0xA2) ACK or NACK messages;
V18 28/05/2014 AK
Multiple ASDU configuration concept using station identifier StationID attribute, which has been added to IEC104sl and IEC104ma element nodes. Existing LinkAddr attribute is used as station identifier for IEC101sl; IEC101ma and IEC103ma element nodes.
All ASDUAddr attributes removed from individual DI/AI/DO/AO nodes;
New concept of protocol setting node element migration to attributes begins with this firmware release; First protocol element nodes to contain setting attributes are: XMLSettings; CommsSettings; ASDUFlags; Broadcast and Periodic;
Information address sequence check across object types introduced. It is essential to use new attribute IOAOverlap if the same information addresses are being reused for DI/AI/DO/AO objects. IOAOverlap is attribute of the newly created XMLSettings element node;
IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocol configuration StartupGIDelay element migrated to become an attribute of the newly created CommsSettings element node;
TranspTypes attribute created for IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocol configuration;
IEC60870-5-101/4 Master protocol configuration OnlineGIDelay element migrated to become an attribute of the newly created CommsSettings element node;
New option to send General Interrogation using broadcast Common address of ASDU can be configured using GI attribute in IEC60870-5-101/4 Broadcast element node;
IEC60870-5-101/4 Master protocol configuration GlobalTimeSync element migrated to become an attribute TimeSync of the newly created Broadcast element node;
IEC60870-5-101/4 Master protocol configuration periodic GIInterval; Group1Interval... Group16Interval; TimeSyncInterval elements migrated to become attributes GI; Group1... Group16; TimeSync respectively of the newly created Periodic element node;
Default values of DIEventBuffSize and AIEventBuffSize elements are automatically initialized to twice the amount of configured objects, instead of fixed value 1024 as used to before;
V17 08/04/2014 AK
Automatic IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocol configuration re-enabled;
Source attribute created for IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocols and Device attribute in DI/AI/DO/AO object elements is no longer mandatory;
GIStartupDelay element created for IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave protocols;
Bit[4] removed from Slave DI qualifier attribute;
AI StartOffset and OffsetDeadband attributes created for IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave AI objects;
Bits[5...6] removed from Slave AI qualifier attribute;
AIEventStartup element created for IEC60870-5-101/3/4 Master protocols;
AI StartOffset; ZeroDeadband; Offset; OffsetDeadband and NonZeroOffset attributes created for IEC60870-5-101/3/4 Master AI objects;
V16 31/03/2014 AK
Supervision functionality added;
UART Timeout; TxDelay and CtrlRdTimeout ranges changed;
UART DataBits; StopBits and TxDelay attributes are no longer mandatory;
Socket node name changed from IPv4 to TCPSERVER and TCPCLIENT and related Mode and Type attributes removed;
New UDP socket node created;
Socket IPport attribute name changed to Port;
New socket attributes ConnectTimeout; Timeout; TxDelay and IdleTimeout created;
IEC60870-5-101 master and slave protocol instances can now be linked to TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT and UDP socket nodes;
Multiple IEC60870-5-104 master protocol instances can now be linked to the same TCPCLIENT socket node;
Bit[3] added to CommsFlags attribute to select either accept or reject new incoming connection to TCP server if linked protocol instance is already connected;
TxAllVarLength node added for IEC60870-5-101 master and slave protocols;
IEC60870-5-104 master OfflineDelay node can have value 0 now and default value changed to 6sec;
Description of the logger LogFlags attribute Bit[4] updated to include IEC60870-5-101 link layer status information recording
V15 26/02/2014 AK
Order of communication protocol instance definition corrected;
UART TxDelay sample value table added;
UART CtrlRdTimer and CtrlRdDebounce attributes created;
ACDAlways and FCBMaskLinkReq attributes created for IEC60870-5-101 Slave protocol;
CommsFlags attribute added for Slave protocol instances;
OfflineDelay default value of the IEC60870-5-101 Master protocol corrected, must be 0 and OfflineDelay element for IEC60870-5-104 Slave protocol created;
DegradedRetries; DegradedTimeout and LinkOnlineDelay nodes added to IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-103 Master protocols;
GlobalGI; AIDeadband and AIPercent nodes added to Master protocol instances;
Master protocol instance nodes GlobalQOC; GlobalDOType and GlobalAOType nodes are renamed to DOQOC; DOType and AOType respectively;
Bit[5] removed from Master protocol instance DO qualifier, use DOType element or individual DO object TypeID attributes for outgoing command ASDU Type selection;
Ignore individual Time tag bit created for Master protocol DI/AI qualifier attributes;
Name attributes added to all nodes;
New Service DI (-5) created allowing to monitor status of the UART Ring Indicator RI pin(9);
New Service DO (-5) created allowing to send Reset command to downstream outstation;
V14 18/01/2014 AK Version control element node added
V13 18/12/2013 AK
Multiple IEC101sl communication protocol instances can share the same serial interface;
OfflineDelay for IEC101sl communication protocol instance added;
Setpoint command configuration added;
GlobalDOType and GlobalAOType nodes added for Master communication protocol instances;
IgnoreTimetags node added for Master communication protocol instances;
New bit in DO/AO qualifier now enables option to accept only Direct-Execute commands;
DO command invert option added, enabled by setting bit[1] in Slave and Master DO.qualifier;
Master communication protocol instance AI processing sequence flowcharts added;
V12 18/11/2013 AK
IEC60870-5-103 Master added;
Unique names for communication protocol instance nodes under CommunicationCfg node;
Link layer and common address of ASDU (CAA) now configured using attributes in communication protocol instance nodes;
CommsFlags attribute created for Master communication protocol instances;
DIEventType and AIEventType nodes created for Slave communication protocol instances;
SpeedUpStarted node removed;
Time-tagged command support added for IEC60870-5-104 Slave and new CommandLatency node created;
DI/AI/DO qualifier attributes are optional from now on;
DI/AI/DO TypeID attributes created;
OffIndex attribute added to Slave communication protocol instance DO object nodes allowing to link ‘On’ and ‘Off’ commands to separate DO objects;
Auto-configuration temporary disabled;
GlobalQOC node added for Master communication protocol instances;
Event logfile configuration moved to lelogger.xml file;
HWLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes created allowing to enable event logging for all communication protocol instances sharing the same hardware interface;
Static and Event DI/AI information recording to event logfiles added;
Slave communication protocol instance AI processing sequence flowcharts added;
